## Chapter 1: All In

### The Scene: Wall Street Poker Night, March 8, 2006

- Setting: Versailles Room, St. Regis Hotel, midtown Manhattan
- **Wall Street Poker Night Tournament** — 100+ elite traders and
  hedge fund managers; charity event raising ~$2M for NYC public
  school math programs (fitting: poker chips stamped with names of
  mathematical gods like **Isaac Newton**)
- Attendees included pro poker players **T.J. Cloutier** and
  **Clonie Gowen**; also **David Einhorn** (Greenlight Capital,
  fundamental investor, 20%+ annual returns)
- The quants — Muller, Asness, Griffin, Weinstein — were so secretive
  that "few people outside the room had ever heard their names," yet
  their decisions controlled "billions of dollars coursing through the
  global financial system every day"

### The Quant Tribe

- Quants used "brain-twisting math and super-powered computers to
  pluck billions in fleeting dollars out of the market"
- Completely indifferent to company "fundamentals" (morale, management
  quality) — that was for **Warren Buffett** and **Peter Lynch**
- Instead: predicted stock movements from numerical variables —
  cheapness relative to market, momentum, combinations thereof
- By early 2000s, quants had come to **dominate Wall Street**, aided
  by theoretical breakthroughs (many Nobel Prize-winning) in
  mathematics applied to financial markets
- Each had a signature strategy:
  - **Griffin**: cheap bonds and distressed companies via math formulas
  - **Muller**: high-frequency buy/sell of stocks using Morgan Stanley
    supercomputers
  - **Asness**: historical backtesting of market trends going back
    decades to detect hidden patterns
  - **Weinstein**: **credit derivatives**, especially **credit default
    swaps** (CDS) — essentially insurance policies on bonds

### The Truth and Alpha

- The quants shared a common obsession: a quasi-mystical goal they
  called **"the Truth"** — a universal secret about how markets work,
  discoverable only through mathematics
- The Truth was the key to **alpha**: the ability to consistently beat
  the market (contrasted with **beta** = plain market returns anyone
  can achieve)
- Alpha = the quants' holy grail; beta = contemptible mediocrity
- The bigger the machine, the more Truth they knew; the more Truth,
  the more they could bet; the more they bet, the richer they got —
  a self-reinforcing loop
- The quest was partly financial, partly about **proof** — each added
  dollar validated that their models had captured something real
- Alpha was so totemic the trade magazine for hedge funds was called
  *Alpha*; Asness named his Goldman-era fund **Global Alpha**; Muller
  helped build a system called **Alphabuilder** at quant firm **BARRA**
- Neil Chriss (U. Chicago + Harvard math degrees, ex-Morgan Stanley,
  ex-Goldman) was building a quant machine at **SAC Capital Advisors**
  under **Steve A. Cohen**

### The Poker Game as Metaphor

- The private poker circle (Muller, Asness, Weinstein, Chriss) held
  games with **$10,000 buy-ins** in Manhattan hotel rooms; regulars
  included **Carl Icahn** (who got his Wall Street start with $4,000
  in poker winnings) and **Marc Lasry** (Avenue Capital, $12B fund)
- Muller in 2004 joined the **World Poker Tour**, won ~$100,000;
  contemplated launching an online poker hedge fund
- Weinstein won a **Maserati** at a 2005 NetJets poker tournament
- The connection: math + competitive gambling instincts + bluffing
  probability trees = the same mental toolkit used to trade markets
- "Skill at poker meant skill at trading. And it potentially meant
  something even more: the magical presence of alpha."
- The poker night outcome: Muller won, beating Asness heads-up with
  a king-high hand despite being an underdog — "The real world works
  like that sometimes" (foreshadowing: lucky outcomes don't persist)

### The Golden Hour — and the Coming Catastrophe

- March 2006 was the height of quant dominance — stocks in a long
  bull run, housing booming, economists spoke of a **"Goldilocks
  economy"**
- **Ben Bernanke** had just taken over the Fed from **Alan Greenspan**;
  his Feb. 2004 speech "**The Great Moderation**" declared volatility
  had been permanently tamed — partly credited to quants' role in
  stabilizing markets by arbitraging away mispricings
- Hedge fund AUM growth: $39B (1990) → $490B (2000) → **$2 trillion
  (2007)**; plus hundreds of billions more at banks (Morgan Stanley,
  Goldman, Citi, Lehman, Bear Stearns, Deutsche)
- AQR: $1B (1998) → $40B (mid-2007). Citadel: $20B+. Renaissance:
  announced $100B fund. Weinstein: $30B in positions at 33.
- Patterson's thesis: the quants "unwittingly primed the bomb and lit
  the fuse for the financial catastrophe that began to explode in
  spectacular fashion in **August 2007**"
- "The result was possibly the biggest, fastest, and strangest
  financial collapse ever seen, and the starting point for the worst
  global economic crisis since the Great Depression"
- The damning irony: **not one quant saw it coming** — despite their
  PhDs, billions in winnings, and decades spent studying every
  statistical quirk in the market

> "I can calculate the motion of heavenly bodies but not the madness
> of people."
> — Isaac Newton, after losing £20,000 in the South Sea Bubble (1720)

