## Chapter 2: The Godfather: Ed Thorp

### Opening Scene — Reno, 1961

- Spring 1961, 5 a.m., small Reno casino — **Ed Thorp** down $100,
  exhausted but unwilling to quit
- Thorp: Ph.D. in physics from UCLA, professor at MIT, age 28
- His system tracked the **ratio of ten-cards remaining** in the deck
  (face cards + natural tens = 16 per deck of 52)
- When tens-heavy deck: dealer bust probability rises (dealers must
  hit on 16 or below); player odds improve sharply
- Called the **hi-lo strategy** — revolutionary breakthrough in
  card counting
- He bet small ($1-2) while testing; when deck went tens-heavy,
  scaled up: $4 → $8 → $16 → $32, backed off at $20, kept winning
- Recovered $100 loss and pocketed profit before dawn
- Dealer's face: "an odd mixture of anger and awe... something
  strange and impossible she could never explain"

### The Mathematical Foundation

- **Law of large numbers**: as sample size grows, observed average
  converges on true probability — 10 coin flips might show 70/30,
  but 10,000 flips always approach 50/50
- A statistical edge means you may lose individual hands but
  *always* come out ahead over enough plays — as long as you
  don't go broke first (the crucial caveat)
- Thorp's system: hundreds of hours of computer time to build;
  not guesswork but rigorous probability mapping

> "It had nothing to do with luck and everything to do with math."

### Thorp's Early Life

- Born Chicago, August 14, 1932; son of WWI army officer
- Showed math ability at 7 (calculating seconds in a year mentally)
- Family moved to Lomita, CA; parents worked defense jobs during
  WWII, left him largely unsupervised
- Classic prodigy mischief: homemade explosives with nitroglycerin
  from a friend's sister at a chemical factory; pipe bombs in Palos
  Verdes wilderness; ham radio; chess by airwaves
- Notorious prank: dropped red dye in Long Beach's largest indoor
  pool, made local papers; faked police spotlight at lovers' lane

### Early Gambling Curiosity

- High school teacher returned from Vegas with cautionary tales —
  "You just can't beat these guys"
- Thorp suspected a *statistical* weakness, the way slot machines
  could be triggered by jiggling handles in just the right way
- **UCLA graduate school, 1955**: began formally thinking about
  using mathematics to describe hidden architecture of seemingly
  random systems — the intellectual seed of quant investing

### The Roulette Problem

- Thorp's first target was roulette, not blackjack
- Precedent: **Albert Hibbs** and **Roy Walford** (U. of Chicago
  roommates, 1949) found defective wheels in Vegas and Reno, made
  thousands — story covered in *Life* magazine
- Thorp's insight: a *perfect* wheel is actually *easier* to
  predict — no defects means ball travels a predictable orbital
  path, like a planet; croupiers take bets *after* ball is in
  motion, so velocity + position data could predict landing octant
- Built a cheap half-scale wheel, timed it in hundredths of a
  second with a stopwatch — too flawed to yield useful data
- Simulated roulette orbits by rolling marbles down V-shaped troughs
  in his kitchen while in-laws watched, baffled

### Meeting Claude Shannon

- Las Vegas visit, 1958: smoothness of casino wheels convinced
  Thorp prediction was feasible; also tested **Roger Baldwin**'s
  blackjack strategy from a 10-page paper in the
  *Journal of the American Statistical Association* (1958)
- Baldwin and colleagues (**James McDermott**, **Herbert Maisel**,
  **Wilbert Cantey**) — known as the **"Four Horsemen"** — used
  desktop calculators for 18 months to map blackjack probabilities;
  never actually tested it in Vegas
- Thorp lost $8.50 testing it, but remained convinced it could be
  improved; contacted Baldwin, got the data, moved to MIT (1959)
- At MIT, Thorp inherited the **C. L. E. Moore Instructor** position
  previously held by **John Nash** (future Nobel laureate,
  subject of *A Beautiful Mind*)
- Summer 1959 at MIT: fed blackjack data into a computer, discovered
  rudimentary elements of a system that could beat the dealer
- Needed a prestigious journal but *Proceedings of the National
  Academy of Sciences* required member sponsorship — sought out
  MIT's mathematics member: **Dr. Claude Elwood Shannon**

### Claude Shannon — Who He Was

- Two landmark intellectual contributions:
  1. **Binary number system applied to electronic circuits** —
     logical 1s and 0s as on/off switches, laying groundwork
     for the modern computer
  2. **Information theory** — how to encode and transmit
     information from A to B
- Shannon's controversial founding claim: "semantic aspects of
  communication are irrelevant to the engineering problem" —
  information is *purely statistical*, devoid of meaning, and
  therefore encodable
- Pre-Shannon science assumed meaning was the fundamental unit
  of communication; Shannon inverted this entirely
- Shannon's home: **"Entropy House"** — named for thermodynamics'
  second law (everything slides toward homogenous randomness);
  in information theory he used entropy to find order within
  apparent chaos
- House: a gadgeteer's paradise — mechanical juggling dolls,
  coin tossers, unicycle (Shannon navigated a tightrope across
  his yard); obsessed with automatons
- The **"ultimate machine"**: a wooden box with a single switch —
  flip it, a hand emerges, turns the switch off, retreats, lid
  closes. **Arthur C. Clarke** visited and called it
  "unspeakably sinister... a machine that does nothing except
  switch itself off"

> "Nothing could be simpler. It is merely a small wooden casket,
> the size and shape of a cigar box, with a single switch on one
> face... There is something unspeakably sinister about a machine
> that does nothing—absolutely nothing—except switch itself off."
> — Arthur C. Clarke on Shannon's "ultimate machine"

### Thorp Meets Shannon

- November 1960: Thorp walked across MIT campus to meet Shannon,
  nervous — Shannon's secretary warned he had only a few minutes
- Thorp rapid-fired his blackjack results; Shannon called it
  "a significant theoretical breakthrough" and agreed to sponsor
  the paper, titled "A Winning Strategy for Blackjack"
- Shannon's one note: rename it — "The Academy can be a bit
  stodgy... How about 'A Favorable Strategy for Twenty-One'?"
- As Thorp stood to leave, Shannon asked if he was working on
  anything else in gambling. Thorp mentioned roulette.
  Shannon lit up: "Really? Continue." They talked for hours.

### The Wearable Computer — Roulette Project

- Thorp and Shannon bought a regulation roulette wheel from Reno
  for $1,500, placed it on a billiard table at Entropy House
- Timed ball using a strobe light synced to a foot-operated switch;
  tracked ball position per revolution
- After trial and error: calculated which **octant** (1/8 of wheel)
  the ball would land in with favorable odds
- 38 pockets = six octants of 5 pockets + two octants of 4 pockets;
  betting all numbers in predicted octant guaranteed positive EV
- Built a **cigarette-pack-sized computer embedded in a shoe**:
  - One toe switch: turned computer on
  - Second toe switch: timed each rotor revolution
  - Computer transmitted prediction via **8 tones to an earpiece**
  - Almost certainly the world's **first wearable computer**
- Fatal flaw: headphone wires kept breaking; Thorp once spotted by
  a woman staring in horror — speaker jutting from ear "like an
  alien insect"
- Project eventually shelved; roulette never yielded the riches
  blackjack did

### The Kelly Criterion

- Shannon pointed Thorp to a 1956 paper by **John Kelly Jr.**,
  a physics researcher at **Bell Laboratories**
- Kelly's question: how much should a gambler with an edge wager
  to maximize growth while avoiding ruin?
- **Martingale/doubling-down flaw**: doubling bets after losses
  (practiced by Casanova et al.) guarantees eventual bankruptcy —
  *gambler's ruin* probability is 100% if you keep playing
- **Kelly's solution**: never go all-in except when odds of winning
  are 100%; bet size is proportional to edge and bankroll
- Formula: "cause his money to grow exponentially" while
  avoiding ruin — bet more when edge is high, less when it shrinks
- Thorp applied Kelly to blackjack: scale bets up when tens-rich
  deck is detected, back off when deck normalizes
- Kelly's insight would later become the **foundation of position
  sizing for all major quant funds**

### Going Public — Fame and Backers

- January 1961: Thorp presented blackjack paper to the
  **American Mathematical Society** under the title
  **"Fortune's Formula: A Winning Strategy for Blackjack"**
- AP reporter picked it up; story ran nationwide —
  **Ed Thorp was suddenly famous**
- Flood of backing offers; accepted $10,000 from a New York
  businessman (disguised as "Mr. X" in *Beat the Dealer*)
- "Mr. X" = **Emmanuel "Manny" Kimmel** — short, white-haired
  racketeer connected to organized crime; numbers games in
  Newark, East Coast horse tracks, co-owner of Kinney Parking
  (64 NYC lots); FBI memo: "lifetime associate of several
  internationally known hoodlums"
- "Mr. Y" = **Eddie Hand**, car-shipping magnate and Kimmel's
  high-stakes gambling partner

### The Vegas Test — Harold's Club, Reno

- Harold's Club: largest casino in downtown Reno —
  higher stakes than the ratty casino of the 5 a.m. test
- $500-maximum tables; won $500 in fifteen minutes
  (bets ranging $25-$250)
- Casino owner **Harold Smith** personally walked over to watch;
  ordered early shuffles to disrupt the count
- Repeated shuffling after only 2 hands severely limited
  opportunity windows, but system still found edges
- Thorp and Kimmel left up **several thousand dollars**
- Over several days, **more than doubled the $10,000 stake**

> "When a lamb goes to the slaughter, the lamb might kill the
> butcher. But we always bet on the butcher."
> — casino owner on TV, unaware Thorp had just beaten him

### Beat the Dealer and the Move to Wall Street

- **Beat the Dealer** published 1962 — instant *NYT* bestseller;
  terrified casino industry
- Casinos now hunted Thorp; he wore disguises; stories circulated
  of card counters getting beaten in casino basements
- 1964: offered drugged coffee at a baccarat table; a nurse friend
  recognized his symptoms as sedation from the emergency room
- That episode ended his casino career:
  **"Thorp immediately set his sights on the biggest casino
  of all: Wall Street"**

---

## Chapter 2 (continued): The Godfather of Quants — Thorp's Warrant Pricing & Princeton/Newport

### Volatility as the Key Variable
- **Volatility** = the quantifiable randomness of a stock's future movement
- Thorp applied **Brownian motion** (Einstein's 1905 random walk) to warrant pricing
  — same law of large numbers that made card counting work: can't predict individual outcomes but can determine probabilities
- Warrant pricing insight: if a warrant is mispriced relative to its likely volatility,
  money can be made — the market was systematically miscalculating this
- Example: IBM at $100, warrant expires in 12 months if IBM hits $110
  — plug in Brownian motion + stock's historical drift to get true warrant value

### Beat the Market (1967)
- Thorp and **Sheen Kassouf** collaborated on *Beat the Market: A Scientific Stock Market System*
- Became one of the most influential quant investing books ever written
- Directly challenged the rising **efficient-market hypothesis (EMH)**, championed by
  **Eugene Fama** at the University of Chicago in the late 1960s
- EMH: market prices reflect all known information; future prices are random (coin flip)
  — the intellectual foundation for the index fund industry
- Thorp dismissed EMH as "academic hot air" — he'd already proven experts wrong at blackjack

### The Efficient Market Hypothesis vs. Quants
- EMH traces to **Louis Bachelier's** bond price observations; codified by Fama
- If EMH is true, active management can't beat the market consistently →
  rational to just buy the index (S&P 500) for low fees
- Thorp's rejoinder: EMH was also the "conventional wisdom" that said you can't beat
  the dealer — and he'd disproven that

### Thorp Meets Buffett (1968)
- With ~10 faculty investors clamoring to join, Thorp needed a proper fund structure
- Summer 1968: drove from Irvine to meet **Warren Buffett** at his Laguna Beach vacation home
- Buffett was winding down **Buffett Limited Partnerships**, distributing assets including
  shares of a New England textile company — **Berkshire Hathaway**
- Buffett explained the **hedge fund** structure: traced to **Benjamin Graham** (*The Intelligent Investor*,
  father of value investing) and **Alfred Winslow Jones**

### Alfred Jones and the First Hedge Fund
- 1940 **Investment Company Act**: exempted fund managers with ≤99 wealthy investors
  (≥$1M assets) from most regulations — the legal loophole behind hedge funds
- **Alfred Winslow Jones**: Australian-born Fortune magazine writer, founded
  **A. W. Jones & Co.** in 1949 with $100,000 ($40K his own) — the first true hedge fund
- Jones's model: long some stocks + short others to hedge the portfolio; used leverage
  to amplify returns; charged 20% performance fee; domiciled offshore
- Returns: **670% over ten years** vs. 358% for the top mutual fund of the era
- Jones was a "primitive quant" — used statistical analysis to manage risk
- By 1968, there were **140 hedge funds** in the U.S. (per SEC survey); George Soros
  was among the new rock-star managers emerging in the bull market

### Princeton/Newport Partners Founded (1969)
- Thorp met **Jay Regan**, a Dartmouth philosophy major at Philadelphia brokerage
  Butcher & Sherrerd, who'd read *Beat the Market* and wanted in
- Deal: Thorp stays in Newport Beach teaching at UC Irvine, works on strategies;
  Regan sets up in Princeton, handles Wall Street relationships
- Originally called **Convertible Hedge Associates**; renamed **Princeton/Newport Partners** in 1975
- Launched late 1969; near-immediate success:
  - 1970: +3% vs. S&P −5%
  - 1971: +13.5% vs. S&P +4%
  - 1972: +26% vs. S&P +14.3%

### Convertible Bond Arbitrage
- Thorp's scan of hundreds of warrants found most were **overpriced** — investors too
  optimistic about warrants expiring in the money (behavioral bias)
- Strategy: **short overpriced warrants** + **buy equivalent stock** as hedge
  — if stock rose unexpectedly, long stock position covered the loss
- Formula calculated exact hedge ratio (how much stock to hold per warrant shorted)
- Best case: warrant declines + stock rises → profit on both legs
- This became known as **convertible bond arbitrage** — one of the most successful
  trading strategies ever devised; later launched thousands of hedge funds including
  **Citadel Investment Group** (Ken Griffin)
- Thorp and Kassouf were first to quantify the hedge ratio precisely
- Strategy evolved into **delta hedging** — delta captures change in relationship
  between stock and warrant/option price; now universal on Wall Street

### The Law of One Price and Arbitrage
- **Law of One Price (LOP)**: identical assets should trade at same price everywhere
  (adjusted for transport/tax differences)
- **True arbitrage**: buy asset cheap in one market, simultaneously sell dear in another
  — virtually riskless profit; e.g., gold at $1,000 in NY vs. $1,050 in London
- Pure arb opportunities are rare and hidden; quants use math to find them
- Thorp's convertible arb was a sophisticated form: not pure arb but close enough
  when properly hedged

### Kelly Criterion Applied to Trading
- Thorp sized positions using the **Kelly criterion** (from his blackjack days)
- Kelly tells you exactly how much to bet given known edge and odds
- Aggressive when opportunities were rich (deck full of face cards); conservative otherwise
- Also maintained paranoid tail-risk awareness: earthquakes, nuclear bombs, meteors —
  "out-of-the-blue events" that could blow up a trade
- This risk discipline was the core of his long-term success — a lesson later quants ignored

### Black-Scholes Formula (1973)
- 1973: Thorp received a letter from **Fischer Black** (U. Chicago) with a draft paper
  co-authored with **Myron Scholes** on option pricing
- **Black-Scholes** independently arrived at the same result as Thorp's warrant formula
  using similar Brownian motion / random walk assumptions
- Thorp programmed it into his HP computer — matched his own formula's output closely
- Black had read *Beat the Market* and was aware of Thorp and Kassouf's delta hedging
- Black-Scholes was destined to revolutionize Wall Street — compared by Patterson
  to Einstein's relativity: transformative and eventually destructive

> "The stock price follows a random walk in continuous time." — Black & Scholes, 1973

- April 26, 1973: **Chicago Board Options Exchange (CBOE)** opened — one month before
  Black-Scholes paper published; Texas Instruments released a handheld calculator
  that could run the formula
- The quant revolution had officially begun
- Scholes and **Robert Merton** (MIT, stochastic calculus) won the Nobel Prize;
  Black had died before Nobel consideration
- Thorp never received formal credit despite devising essentially the same formula —
  but made hundreds of millions using it

### The Fatal Flaw in Black-Scholes
- Black-Scholes assumed stock prices follow continuous Brownian motion (bell curve)
- This meant the model focused on **most likely moves** — the center of the curve —
  and largely **ignored fat tails** (big sudden price jumps)
- Big jumps treated as virtually impossible — "like a drunk suddenly teleporting across Paris"
- Reality: markets DO make huge leaps — panics, scandals, drug failures, investor herding
- Seasoned quants like Thorp understood this and adjusted (Kelly + tail-risk paranoia)
- Less experienced quants began to treat the model as reality itself:
  "hall-of-mirrors-like, it became difficult to tell the difference between
  the model and the market itself"

### Princeton/Newport's Track Record
- Mid-1970s hot streak: **double-digit returns for 11 straight years** (after 20% fees)
- Never had a down year or down quarter from inception
- 1974 (S&P −26%, worst since Great Depression): Princeton/Newport +9.7%
- *Wall Street Journal* front page, 1974: "Playing the Odds: Computer Formulas Are
  One Man's Secret to Success in the Market"

> "Reliable brokerage-house sources close to the funds say they have averaged better
> than 20 percent a year in net asset growth." — WSJ, 1974

- By November 1985: managing ~$130 million (from $1.4M at launch)
- 1982: Thorp quit UC Irvine to manage money full-time

