## Chapter 3 (begins): The Stat Arb Revolution — Bamberger, Tartaglia, Shaw

### Gerry Bamberger Invents Statistical Arbitrage
- 1985: Thorp met **Gerry Bamberger**, a Morgan Stanley programmer who'd just quit
- Bamberger: Orthodox Jew from Long Island, Columbia computer science degree, joined
  Morgan Stanley 1980 to support block trading desk
- Block trading desk handled 10,000+ share institutional orders; used "pairs strategy"
  to minimize risk (long GM, short Ford as hedge)
- Bamberger's software tracked relative positions of pairs in real time

### The Pairs Trading Discovery
- Observation: large block trades temporarily pushed one stock's price while the pair's
  price barely moved — **spread** between the two widened abnormally
- Example: GM typically $10, Ford $5; big GM buy order → GM rises to $10.50,
  Ford stays at $5; spread widens temporarily
- Strategy: **short the stock that moved up** relative to its pair, wait for reversion;
  long the stock that didn't move as protection
- This is **statistical arbitrage (stat arb)**: exploit mean-reversion in related stock pairs
- "The old game of buy low, sell high — with a quant twist"

### Bamberger's Stat Arb at Morgan Stanley
- Early 1983: Morgan gave Bamberger $500K and a small team on the equity desk
- Rapid growth: $500K → $4M (Sept 1983) → $10M (early 1984) → $15M (Oct 1984)
  → **$30M book by 1985**
- Morgan's brass took the operation away from Bamberger, handed it to
  **Nunzio Tartaglia**, a physicist-turned-trader (Yale physics M.S., then Jesuits,
  then Ph.D. astrophysics at U. Pittsburgh, then Wall Street via Merrill Lynch)
- Bamberger, outraged, quit

### APT (Automated Proprietary Trading) Under Tartaglia
- Tartaglia renamed the group **Automated Proprietary Trading (APT)**; moved to
  40-foot room on the 19th floor of Morgan's Exxon Building HQ in midtown Manhattan
- Linked to NYSE's **SuperDOT** (Super Designated Order Turnaround) for computerized trades
- APT at times accounted for **5% of daily NYSE volume**
- Results under Tartaglia: $6M year 1, **$40M in 1986**, **$50M in 1987**
- CIA-like secrecy helped build legendary status

### David Shaw Enters — and Exits
- 1986: Tartaglia hired **David Shaw** (Stanford-educated Columbia computer science professor)
  to head APT's technology; expert in **parallel processing**
- Shaw wanted to develop his own trading strategies; Tartaglia blocked him
- September 1987: Shaw presented parallel processing and bond-arb strategies
  to senior management — APT traders furious (programmers weren't supposed to think about trading)
- Shaw proposed a new scientific lab for quantitative/computational finance;
  idea rejected; Tartaglia unwilling to share the platform
- Shaw quit, started **D. E. Shaw** with $28 million — became one of world's most
  successful hedge funds; core strategy: statistical arbitrage
- "One of the most significant losses of talent in Morgan Stanley history"

### APT's Collapse and Stat Arb's Spread
- 1988: Morgan cut APT's capital from $900M to $300M; Tartaglia levered up to **8:1**
- By 1989, APT hemorrhaging money; Tartaglia forced out; APT shut down
- Bamberger meanwhile joined **Princeton/Newport Partners** via colleague Fred Taylor;
  Thorp backed a fund called **BOSS Partners** (acronym: Bamberger and Oakley Sutton
  Securities — "Oakley" and "Sutton" being Thorp and Regan's middle names)
- BOSS launched with $5M; ~30% return year 1; grew to $100M by 1988
- BOSS hit dry spell in 1988; Bamberger wound it down, moved to SUNY Buffalo to teach

### Stat Arb's Legacy
- Bamberger and Tartaglia's alumni **fanned out across Wall Street**, spreading stat arb to:
  - Goldman Sachs
  - **Renaissance Technologies** (Robert Frey, former APT researcher, brought it to Jim Simons)
  - **Peter Muller** (Morgan Stanley, then his own fund — more robust version)
  - **Ken Griffin / Citadel** (watched Thorp carefully, adopted the strategy)
- **Blair Hull**: MIT blackjack card counter, read *Beat the Dealer* and *Beat the Market*;
  parlayed $25K casino winnings into Chicago options trading career;
  founded **Hull Trading** (1985), sold to Goldman Sachs for **$531M in 1999**
- Stat arb became one of the most popular strategies on Wall Street —
  "too popular, as its practitioners would discover in August 2007"

---

## Chapter 4 (continued): The Godfather of Quants / Black Monday

### Portfolio Insurance and the Birth of LOR

- **Hayne Leland**'s insight: a put option on a *portfolio* of stocks could insure against
  decline — risk becomes quantifiable and manageable
- **Leland O'Brien Rubinstein Associates (LOR)** formed 1981 with **Mark Rubinstein**
  and **John O'Brien**; used the **Black-Scholes formula** as guidepost
- Became far more powerful after Chicago Mercantile Exchange launched **S&P 500 index
  futures** in April 1982 — LOR could replicate portfolio insurance by shorting index futures
- By autumn 1987, LOR covered **$50 billion** in institutional assets; including copycats,
  total equity backed by portfolio insurance ~**$100 billion**

### Black Monday — October 19, 1987

- Dow had gained **40%** through late August 1987 — Reagan boom, Japanese capital flood,
  new Fed chairman, junk bond era
- By mid-October, market had already tumbled 15%; sign at Shearson Lehman Brothers
  block desk: **"To the Lifeboats"**
- Monday Oct 19: S&P futures at the Merc (15 min ahead of NYSE) dropped **14 points**
  before NYSE opened — signaling a 70-point Dow slump
- **Feedback loop mechanism**: portfolio insurers sold futures → drop triggered index arbs
  to short stocks → stocks fell → portfolio insurers forced to sell more futures
  → arbs overwhelmed → futures and stocks fell in unison
- **Fischer Black** at Goldman Sachs watched with fascination; trader Robert Jones reported
  a sell order that never filled — "Wow, really? This is history in the making!"
- Final 75 minutes: Dow slid **300 points**, finishing down **508 points** at 1738.74 —
  triple the largest single-day drop in history, equivalent to a ~1,500-point drop today
- Carnage spread globally overnight: Tokyo, Hong Kong, Paris, Zurich, London; Tuesday
  morning the blue-chip average opened down **more than 30%** before the Fed pumped
  liquidity and the Dow recovered 102 points that day, then 186.84 the next

### Thorp's Response During the Crash

- **Ed Thorp** (Princeton/Newport, Newport Beach) watched market lose 23% by lunch Monday
- Quickly diagnosed: portfolio insurance was the cause of the feedback spiral
- Tuesday morning: massive gap opened between S&P futures and cash — classic arb signal
- Most arbs were terrified; Thorp was determined — ordered head trader:
  **"Buy $5 million worth of index futures at the market and short $10 million worth of stocks"**
- Trader initially refused: "Can't, the market's frozen"
- Thorp threatened to do the trades in his own personal account and cut the firm out of profits
- Trader executed ~60% of short sales; trade pocketed **more than $1 million in profits**
- Princeton/Newport closed October flat; earned **27% for the year** vs. S&P 500's 5%

> "If you don't fill these orders I'm going to do them in my own personal account. I'm going
> to hang you out to dry." — **Ed Thorp** to his head trader, Oct 20, 1987

### Aftermath and the Quant Crisis of Faith

- Portfolio insurance roundly blamed for the crash — quants' own product triggered
  the meltdown it was designed to prevent
- **Eugene Fama's efficient market theory** instantly questioned: how could the market be
  "right" one day, then collapse 23% on virtually no new information, then recover the next?
- Quant retort from **Jens Carsten Jackwerth** (UC Berkeley) and **Mark Rubinstein** (1995
  paper): Black Monday was statistically impossible — a **"27-standard-deviation event"**,
  probability of 10 to the **160th power**
  - "Even if one were to have lived through the entire 20 billion year life of the universe
    and experienced this 20 billion times... a virtual impossibility"
- This mathematical denial exposed the fatal flaw: models assumed **Brownian motion** and
  random walks — but markets leapt like "Mexican jumping beans," not in tiny incremental ticks
- The haunting fear: **"Was there a worm in the apple, a fatal flaw in the quants' theory?"**
  — would recur from 1987 all the way to August 2007

---

### Benoit Mandelbrot — The Flaw Identified Decades Earlier

- The fatal flaw had already been found by **Benoit Mandelbrot**, one of the world's most
  brilliant mathematicians

**Biography:**
- Born 1924; family were **Lithuanian Jews** living in Warsaw, moved to Paris 1936
- Uncle **Szolem Mandelbrojt** was prominent in Paris mathematical elite; Benoit studied
  under him
- 1940: Nazi invasion; family fled to Tulle in southwest France
- Near-miss: French partisans blew up a German outpost; witness identified attacker by a
  distinctive Scottish-design jacket — the same one Mandelbrot wore. He went into hiding
  for a year until Paris was liberated (1944)
- Freedom from Parisian academic competition nurtured his ability to **visualize complex
  geometric images** and make intuitive leaps — his defining intellectual style
- Took entrance exam for École Normale Supérieure and **École Polytechnique** cold, with
  no preparation — solved complex algebra/geometry problem with geometric intuition instead
  of calculation — **top score in France**
- Ph.D. 1952; worked briefly with psychologist **Jean Piaget**; spent a year at Princeton's
  **Institute for Advanced Study** (1953); joined **IBM's Thomas J. Watson Research Center** 1958

### The Cotton Prices Discovery

- 1961: Mandelbrot invited to give a talk at Harvard by economics professor
  **Hendrik Houthakker**, who studied cotton prices
- Upon entering Houthakker's office, Mandelbrot saw a diagram on the blackboard — a convex
  V opening to the right — and immediately recognized it: *it exactly matched a diagram
  he had prepared for his own lecture on income distributions*
- Houthakker had been trying to fit cotton prices into standard **Brownian motion** models;
  nothing worked — prices moved too erratically for the bell curve

> "I've had enough. I try to measure the volatility. It changes all the time. Everything
> changes. Nothing is constant. It's a mess of the worst kind." — **Hendrik Houthakker**

- Houthakker handed Mandelbrot a cardboard box of **IBM punch cards** containing cotton
  price data going back more than a century (New York Cotton Exchange records)
- Mandelbrot ran the data at IBM's supercomputers + gathered wheat prices, railroad stocks,
  interest rates — everywhere he looked: **huge leaps where they didn't belong**, on the
  outer edges of the bell curve

### Fat Tails — "The Variation of Certain Speculative Prices"

- Mandelbrot's paper (published as IBM internal research report) was a direct attack on
  normal distributions used to model markets
- Key finding: **"the empirical distributions of price changes are usually too 'peaked'
  relative to samples"** from standard distributions; **"Large price changes are much more
  frequent than predicted"**
- Solution borrowed from French mathematician **Paul Lévy** (whom Mandelbrot studied under
  in Paris): **Lévy distributions**, where a *single sample can radically change the entire curve*
  - Unlike normal distributions (1,001st person's height barely shifts the average),
    a Lévy distribution can be overturned by one wild shift
  - Mandelbrot's analogy: 1,000 shots from a blindfolded archer cluster near the target;
    the 1,001st may fly wildly off — *all previous results overturned by one dramatic shift*
- When plotted: distribution "bubbles out" on both ends of the bell curve — coined **"fat tails"**
- Fat tails explained Black Monday: a **27-sigma event** isn't impossible if you're in a
  Lévy/fat-tail world rather than a Gaussian world

### Reception and Rejection

- 1963: **Paul Cootner** (MIT finance professor) assembling *The Random Character of Stock
  Market Prices* (the same book Thorp read when pricing warrants) contacted Mandelbrot to
  include his paper — then attacked it in a **vicious five-page critique**
- Cootner: Mandelbrot "promises us not utopia but blood, sweat, toil, and tears"
- Mainstream rejection: approach too simplistic, too inconvenient, incapable of predicting
  prices, like trying to forecast a Mexican jumping bean
- Critics acknowledged it may work for brief volatile periods but argued long-term prices
  move in a more orderly Brownian fashion — empirically, market indexes do trend upward
- Mandelbrot's counter: **short-period gyrations are wildly enough to cause massive,
  potentially crippling losses** to leveraged investors — the long run is irrelevant if
  you're wiped out first
- **Nassim Nicholas Taleb** later extended Mandelbrot's logic: investors who believe in
  random walks are "**fooled by randomness**"; the wild swings are **"black swans"** —
  named for the long-held Western belief that all swans are white, exploded when black
  swans were discovered in Australia
- **LTCM preview**: a decade after Black Monday, **Long-Term Capital Management** —
  whose partners included **Myron Scholes** and **Robert Merton** — lost billions in weeks
  (summer 1998), requiring a Fed-organized bailout by **Alan Greenspan**. Partners claimed
  they'd have profited if they could have held longer. Patterson's verdict: "LTCM went all
  in and lost."

### The Volatility Smile — Black Monday's Permanent Scar

- After the crash, options traders noticed **deep out-of-the-money puts** (bets on huge
  declines) priced unusually high vs. puts near current stock price
- Charts showed a curvy kink — dubbed the **"volatility smile"** — the market's embedded
  memory of Black Monday
- Under Black-Scholes, the smile *shouldn't exist* — it implies arb profits from selling
  overpriced puts. But traders refused to sell them, terrified of another crash
- **Emanuel Derman** (Goldman Sachs, author of *My Life as a Quant*):

> "I realized that the existence of the smile was completely at odds with Black and Scholes's
> 20-year-old foundation of options theory... The smile, therefore, poked a small hole deep
> into the dike of theory that sheltered options trading."

- The volatility smile persists to this day — proof that markets permanently repriced
  tail risk after experiencing it once

---

### Princeton/Newport Partners Raided — Thorp's Black Swan

- **December 1987**: 50 armed federal marshals raided Princeton/Newport's Princeton office
  (above a Häagen-Dazs shop) seeking documents on dealings with **Michael Milken**'s junk
  bond empire at **Drexel Burnham Lambert**
- Prosecutor: **Rudolph Giuliani**, U.S. Attorney for Southern District of New York
- Goal: pressure P/NP employees to flip and testify against Milken
- August 1989: Manhattan jury convicted **5 Princeton/Newport executives** (including Regan)
  of 63 felony counts re: illegal stock trading plots
- Thorp — 2,000 miles away in Newport Beach, unaware of the Princeton dealings — was
  **never charged**
- June 1991: federal appeals court **tossed out the racketeering convictions**; early 1992
  prosecutors dropped the case; no P/NP employee spent a day in prison
- But the damage was done: investors pulled out; Thorp couldn't keep the ship steady
  amid the controversy — **Princeton/Newport Partners was finished**

### Thorp Uncovers Madoff

- 1991: as a consultant reviewing a company's investment portfolio, Thorp noticed a fund
  with **20%+ returns every single year** throughout the 1980s — better than anything he'd
  ever seen, including Princeton/Newport
- Fund supposedly traded stock options rapidly from its office in New York's
  **Lipstick Building** on Third Avenue
- Thorp reviewed trading records — the fund reported buying **123 call options on P&G
  on April 16, 1991**, but only **20 P&G options total** had traded that day on any exchange
- Similar discrepancies in IBM, Disney, Merck options — the reported trades were *impossible*
- Thorp concluded it was fraud; advised the client to pull its money out of
  **Bernard L. Madoff Investment Securities**
- In late 2008, **Bernard Madoff**'s fund was revealed as the **greatest Ponzi scheme of all
  time**, bilking investors out of tens of billions

---

## Chapter 3 (cont.): The Poker Player — Ken Griffin

### Griffin Discovers Convertible Bonds
- **Susquehanna International Group** cut into Griffin's early winnings, revealing
  the market was more complex than he'd assumed
- Discovered **Ed Thorp**'s *Beat the Market* — found it had already filtered into
  academia and was being taught in finance classrooms
- Wrote software to flag mispriced convertible bonds; wired Harvard dorm room
  with satellite dish, routing cable through elevator shaft to get real-time quotes
  (fourth-floor window permanently cracked in Cambridge winters)

### Griffin's First Fund — Black Monday Windfall
- Summer 1987: pitching convertible bond ideas at First National Bank of Palm Beach;
  retiree **Saul Golkin** handed over $50K after 20-minute pitch ("I've got to run
  to lunch, I'm in for fifty")
- Raised $265,000 total → launched **Convertible Hedge Fund #1**
  (near-identical name to Thorp's Convertible Hedge Associates)
- October 19, 1987 — **Black Monday**: short positions jackpotted as stocks fell
  further than warrants; Griffin made money while Wall Street was "clobbered"
- Quickly raised $750,000 for **Convertible Hedge Fund #2**

### Building Citadel
- 1989: at 19, convinced **Merrill Lynch** convertible bond expert **Terrence O'Connor**
  to open an institutional trading account — standard accounts ran ~$100M;
  Griffin had a few hundred thousand
- Typical Wall Street reaction to cold calls: *"You're running two hundred grand
  out of your dorm room? Don't ever call me again." Slam.*
- Pre-graduation, met **Justin Adams** (Triple I manager, Army Special Forces vet);
  Adams connected him to **Frank Meyer**, investor in Triple I and Princeton/Newport
- Meyer on Griffin's edge: *"He went around to every major stock loan company
  and ingratiated himself, and because he was so unusual they gave him good rates."*
- Set up in Chicago late 1989 with ~$1M; posted **70% return in first year**
- Meyer helped Griffin launch his own fund; the name came from a staff vote:
  **Citadel**. By 1990 it was ready for battle.

---

## Chapter 4: The Mathematician — Peter Muller

### Origin Story
- Age 10, on European family tour: noticed dollar exchange rates differed by country;
  asked if he could buy deutschmarks in London, exchange in Germany for profit —
  intuitively grasped **arbitrage**
- Born 1963, grew up Wayne, NJ; math aptitude, games obsessive (Scrabble, chess,
  backgammon); designed backgammon program in high school so effective his math
  teacher accused him of cheating
- **Princeton**: studied theoretical mathematics, played piano in jazz band

### BARRA and the Quant World
- Post-Princeton 1985, drifted to California; played electric piano for rhythmic
  gymnastics team ($200/month rent, gun-happy roommate)
- Applied to **BARRA Inc.** (Berkeley financial engineering firm) for a Fortran
  programmer role — had never taken a finance class, considered himself a socialist
- Nearly canceled interview after finding a cigarette butt in the bathroom;
  learned BARRA didn't allow smoking — the butt was from a visitor

### BARRA's Founder: Barr Rosenberg
- **BARRA** founded 1974 by **Barr Rosenberg**, Berkeley econ professor, pioneer of
  applying modern portfolio theory to real-world portfolio construction
- Key insight: stocks are driven by multiple *factors* (industry, market cap,
  oil prices, interest rates) — just as patients respond differently to drugs,
  stocks exhibit strange, seemingly inexplicable behavior over time
- Built **Fundamental Risk Management Service** — computerized program forecasting
  stock behavior from earnings, industry, market cap, trading activity
- By time Muller arrived, thousands of managers were using BARRA's quant strategies
- Rosenberg left in 1985 to found **Rosenberg Institutional Equity Management** in
  Orinda, CA (eventually managed several billion); later drifted to teaching
  Buddhism at the Nyingma Institute in Berkeley

### Models Can Fool Even the Best
- Muller's first BARRA project: decomposing stock returns into factor components
- Rosenberg reviewed flawed data, confidently identified "oil prices" and
  "interest rates" — but Muller had screwed up the math; corrected version
  yielded the same confident interpretations
- Lesson: quant models could give false confidence; even high-powered math
  had "a bit of the witch doctor" — "a voodoolike hunt for prophecies in
  chicken entrails"

### Muller at BARRA — Culture and Poker
- Casual Berkeley atmosphere: long lunches, jazz band, monthly full-moon runs
- Devoured **Eugene Fama**, **Fischer Black**, **Robert Merton** — the canon of
  modern portfolio theory
- Discovered poker at the **Oaks Card Room** in Emeryville; 10-15 hours/week,
  once played 6pm Friday to 10am Sunday without stopping; fell asleep at a stoplight
- 1989: assigned to help **Renaissance Technologies** (**Jim Simons**) solve a cash
  management problem for the **Medallion** fund; Renaissance offered him a job —
  he turned it down, still believing in **Fama's efficient-markets hypothesis**

### Muller Leaves BARRA for Morgan Stanley
- 1991: BARRA went public; Muller felt company lost energy; proposed an internal
  hedge fund using BARRA's own quant models (staffed by poker buddies)
- Management killed the idea post-IPO; CEO **Andrew Rudd** redirected him to
  build client-facing return-forecasting models
- Helped design **Alphabuilder** — PC-based software for analyzing expected
  stock portfolio returns — then quit
- Joined **Morgan Stanley**, setting up a quantitative trading group
- Culture shock: promised office and data sources on day one; neither appeared;
  a trader grabbed his phone mid-call to bark orders to Chicago and Tokyo
- Flowers sent by a friend were "raw meat to the grizzled traders":
  *Look at the California quant boy and his pretty flowers.*

---

## Chapter 5: The Professor — Cliff Asness

### Eugene Fama's Classroom, September 1989
- **Eugene Fama**, University of Chicago, opened class with: *"Everything I'm
  about to say isn't true."* Wrote on the board: *Efficient-market hypothesis.*

> "The evidence shows that trying to pick stocks is a complete waste of time. And money. Wall Street is full of salesmen trying to convince people to give them a buck. But there's never been a study in history showing active managers consistently beat the market. It just does not in the data. Managers have good runs, but it usually does just come down to dumb luck."
> — Eugene Fama

- On Warren Buffett: *"There do seem to be a few outliers that are impossible
  to explain... These freak geniuses may be out there, but I don't know who they
  are. Who knows, maybe they'll lose it all next year."*
- Coin-flip analogy: give 10,000 people a quarter, flip 20 rounds, 3-4 remain
  undefeated — on Wall Street they'd be "expert coin flippers drenched in alpha"
- Fama admitted EMH is a model, not physics: *"The market is far more unstable
  and unpredictable... There's always the chance we're wrong."* Then: *"Although
  I'm virtually certain that we're right. God knows the market is efficient."*

### Fama's Intellectual Lineage
- **Harry Markowitz** (former Chicago student): diversification maximizes returns
  while lowering risk — quant-speak for "don't put all eggs in one basket"
- **William Sharpe** (Markowitz protégé): developed **beta** — stock sensitivity
  to broader market volatility; beta=1 moves with market, beta=2 is highly
  volatile (tech), low beta = blue chips (AT&T)
- **Louis Bachelier** (obscure French mathematician): bond prices move by random
  walk; *"The mathematical expectation of the speculator is zero"*
- **Maurice Kendall** (LSE statistician, 1952 speech): analyzed stock indexes,
  wheat/cotton prices — found no patterns; data looked "like a wandering one,
  almost as if once a week the Demon of Chance drew a random number"
- **Paul Samuelson** (MIT, 1954): rediscovered Bachelier via Leonard "Jimmie"
  Savage's postcard; concluded investors were wasting their time
- Samuelson's students: **Robert Merton** (co-creator, Black-Scholes),
  **Burton Malkiel** (*A Random Walk Down Wall Street*)
- **CRSP** — Chicago's Center for Research in Security Prices — gave Fama the
  data firepower to formalize EMH in 1969

### EMH — Core Logic and Paradoxes
- **EMH**: all known information is instantly priced into stocks; future info
  is unknowable → price movements are a random walk / Brownian motion
- The piranha paradox: efficient markets require hungry investors hunting
  inefficiencies, but if markets were perfectly efficient, there'd be no
  inefficiencies to hunt → no piranhas → no efficiency. Circular.
- EMH's dangerous implication: it makes it *impossible* to call any market
  a bubble. Nasdaq at 5,000 in 2000? Not a bubble per EMH. Housing 2005?
  Also not a bubble. *"Such ugly phenomena simply didn't fit within the
  elegant models spawned by the quants."*
- **Monte Carlo simulations** (used by Fidelity, T. Rowe Price for retirement
  planning) baked in random-walk assumptions — modeled a 50% crash as a
  virtual impossibility, precisely the kind of event that actually occurred

### How Quants Used EMH
- Most quants believed markets were only *partly* efficient — a coin with
  a small flaw: 52 heads per 100 flips instead of 50
- **Fischer Black**: "the market is more efficient on the banks of the Charles
  River than the banks of the Hudson" (said after joining Goldman Sachs)
- EMH gave quants a benchmark: every deviation from perfect efficiency was
  a profit opportunity; best models + fastest computers win
- EMH also gave quants a **model of the Truth** — a target equilibrium state
  that prices constantly gravitate toward; deviations = detectable, exploitable

### Fama-French Three-Factor Model (1992)
- Asness arrived at Chicago just as Fama and colleague **Kenneth French** were
  developing their landmark paper — arguably "the most important academic
  finance research of the last two decades"
- Target: overturn **CAPM** (Capital Asset Pricing Model), which held that
  **beta** alone determined a stock's expected return (more risk = more reward)
- Fama/French found CAPM was incomplete — beta alone didn't explain returns

### Cliff Asness — Background
- Born October 1966, Queens, NY; grew up Roslyn Heights, Long Island
- Listless teenager — obsessed with girls and comic books; violent temper
  (once threw a chess rival into a van repeatedly in a parking lot)
- Wharton undergrad; research assistant to professor **Andrew Lo** (later MIT)
  in portfolio theory — found it fascinating, switched to finance + CS
- Canceled LSAT appointment; chose Chicago for PhD after Stanford didn't fly
  him out for a visit (Chicago did, on a beautiful spring day — "the ultimate
  bait and switch")

<!-- pp. 101-120 -->

## Chapter 5 (continued): The Quant God — Asness & the Three-Factor Model

### Fama-French Detonate CAPM

- **Fama and French** ran supercomputer tests on decades of stock market
  return data (1963–1990) to determine how much **beta** actually drove
  returns — their conclusion: **none**
- Called beta's irrelevance "lobbing a Molotov cocktail into the most
  sacred tent of modern portfolio theory" — decades of research
  flat-out wrong
- Two factors that *did* drive returns: **value** and **size**
  - **Size**: measured by **market capitalization** (share price × shares
    outstanding); small stocks consistently outperformed large ones
  - **Value**: measured by **price-to-book ratio** (share price vs. net
    worth of assets minus liabilities); **value stocks** (low P/B, cheap,
    unloved) outperformed **growth stocks** (high P/B, expensive, loved)
    over almost any time horizon back to 1963
- The pizza analogy: mushroom pizzas (value) fall out of favor, price
  drops; eventually the discount grows so wide people switch back and
  mushroom rises — the law of large numbers favors the unloved

### The Quant Community's Reaction

- Impact on quant world compared to **Martin Luther** nailing the
  Ninety-Five Theses — the holy **CAPM** was no longer the Truth
- **Fischer Black** (by then at Goldman Sachs) leveled the sharpest
  rebuttal: "Fama and French … misinterpret their own data"
- **William Sharpe** argued the sample period artificially favored value
  because value stocks happened to recover strongly after the 1970s
  oil-crisis beating
- Despite pushback, the **Fama-French three-factor model** took hold —
  and opened floodgates for new quant research
- Sinister longer-term effect: more and more quants crowded into the
  same value/size strategies, planting seeds for a future meltdown

### Asness Discovers Momentum

- In 1990, **Cliff Asness** (Fama's teaching assistant, called "the
  smartest student they'd ever seen") approached Fama to pitch a
  dissertation topic that directly challenged EMH: **momentum**
- Observation from data: stocks that were falling kept falling more than
  fundamentals justified; rising stocks kept rising — physics borrowed
  the word **"momentum"** for this
- EMH says momentum *shouldn't exist* — it implies predictability
- Asness, nervous, told Fama his paper would be "pro-momentum"
- Fama's response: **"If it's in the data, write the paper."** — Asness
  called it a remarkable display of intellectual honesty
- Asness found patterns of both long- and short-term momentum in stock
  prices; only later did he realize he had discovered exploitable market
  patterns; at the time he just wanted to graduate

### Asness Joins Goldman Sachs

- In 1992, while completing his dissertation, Asness was recruited by
  **Goldman Sachs Asset Management (GSAM)** — actively building a quant
  brain trust
- Also received an offer from **Pimco** (run by **Bill Gross**, a former
  blackjack card counter who had read **Ed Thorp's** *Beat the Dealer*
  and *Beat the Market*) after Pimco found Asness's paper "OAS Models,
  Expected Returns, and a Steep Yield Curve"
- Chose Goldman over Pimco — proximity to his hometown of Roslyn Heights
  ("You're taking the worse job because you're a mama's boy, huh?"
  quipped the Pimco recruiter)
- In **1994**, age 28, **Clifford Asness, Ph.D.** launched the
  **Quantitative Research Group at Goldman Sachs**

---

## Weinstein Section: Boaz Weinstein's Origin

### Early Life — Chess Prodigy Meets Wall Street

- **Boaz Weinstein** grew up on the Upper East Side of Manhattan —
  surrounded by finance from childhood, unlike Griffin, Muller, and Asness
  who all came from outside the Wall Street ecosystem
- As a boy in the early 1980s, played chess against **Joshua Waitzkin**
  (the boy genius later profiled in *Searching for Bobby Fischer*) at
  the **Manhattan Chess Club** — lost, but was undeterred
- By age 16: national "life master," No. 3 in the U.S. in his age group,
  a few steps from grandmaster
- Weekly ritual: watching *Wall Street Week with Louis Rukeyser*; began
  dabbling in stocks with spare change
- Junior year at **Stuyvesant High School**: won a *Newsday* stock-picking
  contest against 5,000 contestants — winning strategy was a primitive
  arbitrage: short big gainers, buy beaten-down stocks
- Age 15: part-time clerical job at **Merrill Lynch**; spent downtime
  reading research reports looking for tips
- Age 19: landed a part-time job on **Goldman Sachs's high-yield bond
  trading desk** after a bathroom run-in with **David DeLucia**, a junk
  bond trader from his chess club, led to a floor tour and interviews

### University & Intellectual Influences

- 1991: enrolled at **University of Michigan**, majored in **philosophy**
  — drawn to Aristotle's logic and Scottish skeptic **David Hume**
- 1993: picked up **Ed Thorp's** *Beat the Dealer* — loved how card
  counting gave a statistical ability to predict the future; connected
  it to **Mark Twain's** *A Connecticut Yankee in King Arthur's Court*
  (hero saves himself by predicting a solar eclipse from memorized data)
- After graduation 1995: global debt trading desk at **Merrill Lynch**;
  two years later moved to **Donaldson Lufkin Jenrette (DLJ)**, recruited
  by DeLucia — learned nuts and bolts of credit trading in floating-rate
  notes (bonds with variable interest rates)

### Enter Credit Derivatives

- Mid-1990s: financial engineers began creating **derivatives linked to
  credit** — a revolution that changed Wall Street permanently
- Young quants without old-school training could dance circles around
  traditional traders who only worried about whether borrowers would
  repay and where rates would go
- Banks increasingly encouraged traders to push the envelope; hedge fund
  golden age was igniting (Soros, Thorp, etc.)

### Weinstein Joins Deutsche Bank — CDS Pioneer

- **1998**: Weinstein joined **Deutsche Bank**, which was transforming
  from a stodgy commercial bank into a derivatives powerhouse
  - Deutsche was acquiring **Bankers Trust** (a cowboy NY investment bank
    packed with quants), which would make it the world's largest bank
    with $800 billion+ in assets
- His job: trading a then-obscure derivative — **credit-linked notes**,
  which eventually became known as **credit default swaps (CDS)**
- **CDS mechanics** (taught by Deutsche's global credit head
  **Ronald Tanemura**, who cut his teeth at Salomon Brothers in the 1980s):
  - CDS = insurance contracts on loans
  - Buyer pays a **premium** for the right to collect if a borrower
    defaults; seller swaps their exposure to default risk
  - Priced by how much to insure several million in bonds over a period
    (typically 5 years); e.g., $1M to insure $10M of GM debt over 5
    years implies ~10% default probability
  - Trades were "bespoke" — custom OTC deals, no central clearinghouse,
    virtually **zero regulatory oversight** — "that was just the way the
    industry wanted it"
  - Swaps could be resold: a trader who buys GM CDS for $1M could sell
    it for $2M later on purely on *perception* that GM's fate worsened
  - Hundreds of swaps could be written on a single bond; or on baskets
    of thousands of bonds — metastasized to **$60 trillion** a decade later

- When Weinstein joined, only a few notes traded per day; his boss soon
  jumped ship, leaving him as the **only CDS trader at Deutsche Bank
  in New York** — a sleepy backwater that would become one of the most
  powerful weapons in the quant arsenal

---

## LTCM: The First Major Quant Catastrophe

### Founding and Strategy

- **1994**: **John Meriwether** (former star Salomon Brothers bond trader)
  launched **Long-Term Capital Management (LTCM)** — started with $1B
  in investor capital (Feb 24, 1994)
- Dream team: quants from Salomon + future Nobel Prize winners
  **Myron Scholes** and **Robert Merton**
- LTCM described as a "thought experiment" — a laboratory run by
  academics trained in math and economics, rooted in breakthroughs from
  **Harry Markowitz** forward
- Core strategy: **relative-value trades** — bet on pairs of securities
  that drifted out of their natural relationship, profit when the
  relationship restores ("the Truth")

### The Off-the-Run/On-the-Run Trade

- Favorite trade: buy old "**off-the-run**" Treasuries (previously issued,
  lower liquidity) while shorting new "**on-the-run**" Treasuries (freshly
  issued, highly liquid)
- The spread existed because institutions (mutual funds, banks, foreign
  governments) paid a **liquidity premium** for newer bonds — but
  economically the bonds were essentially the same
- Spread was tiny (a few **basis points**) — solution: **massive leverage**
  ("just borrow as much cash as possible, amp up the trade, and you
  basically have a printing press for money")
- Meriwether spent $20M on a state-of-the-art computer system;
  set up in Greenwich, Connecticut

### VAR — The Dangerous Risk Tool

- Risk management tool: **Value-at-Risk (VAR)**, created by J.P. Morgan
  quants in the early 1990s — measured the daily volatility of positions
  and translated that into a dollar amount; a **bell curve** distribution
  based on Brownian motion
- VAR = "the amount of money the bank could lose over a 24-hour period
  within a 95% probability"
- LTCM's 1993 prospectus: "The reduction in volatility through hedging
  could permit the leveraging up of the resulting position to the same
  expected level of volatility as an unhedged position, but with a
  larger expected return" — if you can make risk disappear, you can
  layer on even more leverage without looking reckless

### Ed Thorp's Warning

- A financial engineering firm consulting for LTCM also worked with
  **Ed Thorp** (then running **Ridgeline Partners**, a new stat arb fund
  in Newport Beach, 1994) — suggested Thorp invest in LTCM
- Thorp declined: the academics didn't have enough real-world experience,
  and he'd heard Meriwether was a high roller; passed on the investment

### LTCM's Rise and Fatal Confidence

- Returns: 28% (1994), 43% (1995), 41% (1996), 17% (1997)
- End of 1997: partners so confident they **returned $3 billion** in
  capital to investors — more gains would flow to partners personally;
  many plowed personal wealth into the fund; "all in"
- Every major Wall Street bond desk (Goldman, Lehman, Bear Stearns)
  was imitating LTCM's strategies — crowding that would doom them,
  earning LTCM the nickname **"Salomon North"**

### The Collapse

- First blow: **Salomon Brothers** fixed-income arb desk was shut down
  by new owner **Travelers Group** — Salomon began unwinding positions
  that were often the *same* as LTCM's; cascade of sell orders from
  computer models at similar firms followed
- **August 17, 1998**: **Russia defaulted on its debt** — catastrophic
  **"flight to liquidity"** across global markets
- Investors fled anything risky and piled into the safest, most liquid
  asset: **on-the-run U.S. Treasury bonds** — the very bonds LTCM had
  massively shorted
- LTCM's models said the trades were *more attractive than ever* — the
  piranhas (arbitrageurs) that should have swooped in were nowhere to
  be found

> "Despite the ballyhooed growth in derivatives, there was no liquidity
> in credit markets. There never is when everyone wants out at the same
> time. This is what the models had missed. When losses mount, leveraged
> investors are forced to sell, lest their losses overwhelm them. When
> a firm has to sell in a market without buyers, prices run to the
> extremes beyond the bell curve."
> — Roger Lowenstein, *When Genius Failed*

- By end of August 1998: LTCM lost **$1.9 billion, 44% of its capital**;
  leverage ratio spiked to an estimated **100 to 1**
- Appealed to **Warren Buffett** (nearly bought the portfolio, blocked
  by technicalities) and **George Soros** (refused — LTCM's quant style
  was antithesis of his gut-driven approach)

> "The increasing skill in measuring risk and modeling risk led to the
> neglect of uncertainty at LTCM … They didn't recognize that the model
> is flawed and it neglected this thick tail in the bell curve."
> — George Soros

- Bailout: consortium of **14 U.S. and European banks** organized by
  the **Federal Reserve**; partners lost their life savings
- Broader damage: a black eye for the quants — LTCM's space-age risk
  systems (VAR, hedging models) had failed spectacularly, echoing the
  earlier portfolio insurance debacle; **two strikes against quants**;
  strike three would come in August 2007

### Irony: LTCM's Collapse Rocket-Fueled Weinstein

- LTCM's chaos triggered a **credit derivatives boom** — banks rushed
  to hedge themselves with CDS insurance; **AIG Financial Products**
  (London quant unit) became a major seller of that insurance
- New hedge funds (Citadel copycats) specializing in convertible-bond
  arb used CDS as a better hedge than Thorp's old stock-hedging method
- By late 2000: **nearly $1 trillion** in CDS had been created
- Weinstein — one of the few people who actually understood how they
  worked — went from bit player to **rising star at Deutsche Bank**,
  becoming one of the hottest, highest-paid credit traders on Wall Street

---

## Chapter 5 (cont.): The Quants Take Wall Street

### Brown's Liar's Poker Strategy

- **Peter Brown** (Kidder Peabody quant) cracked Liar's Poker mathematically after being humiliated by traders
- Key insight: challenge requires ~90% confidence — in a 10-person game, right = +$100, wrong = -$900
- Identified two game paths:
  - Path 1: same number bid throughout — virtually impossible to see 14+ of any digit in 10 bills
  - Path 2: someone changes the number around bid 10 — signals they hold 3-4 of that digit, boosting odds of 14+ instances substantially
- Built a **simulator** so quants could practice on home computers; trained for speed
- Optimal tactic: raise bets dramatically when holding 2+ of same digit (e.g., jump from "eight 6s" to "fourteen 7s")
- Execution: quants machine-gunned bids on Kidder's floor — ten 7s, twelve 8s, thirteen 9s — traders dumbfounded, head trader challenged, lost (there were fifteen 9s), then refused to pay, accused quants of cheating
- Result: Liar's Poker **died on Wall Street within a year** as Brown's strategy spread to other firms

### The Quant Wave Into Wall Street

- 1980s: quants flooded in from **BARRA** (Berkeley), **University of Chicago** (Fama/French), military-industrial code-breaking programs
- Enabling conditions: rise of personal computers, volatility from fluctuating inflation/rates, new options and futures exchanges in Chicago and NY
- Physicists, electrical engineers, code breakers — all found math skills translated to finance profits
- Financial engineering programs cropped up: Columbia, Princeton, Stanford, Berkeley
- First wave went to **Salomon Brothers**, **Morgan Stanley**, **Goldman Sachs**
- Renegades broke off to form secretive hedge funds in the tradition of **Ed Thorp** — one group emerged in a small Long Island town: **Renaissance Technologies**

---

## Chapter 6: The Medallion

### Setauket, Long Island — Renaissance's Unlikely Home

- Renaissance HQ sits on Route 25A in **East Setauket**, Long Island — the same road where George Washington stayed at Roe's Tavern on April 22, 1790
- Setauket was the center of the **Culver Spy Ring** during the Revolutionary War:
  - **Robert Townsend** posed as Tory merchant in Manhattan, passed info to Setauket innkeeper → farmer → whaleboat captain **Caleb Brewster** → **Major Benjamin Tallmadge** → Washington
- Patterson's framing: fitting that the world's most secretive hedge fund, founded by a former government code breaker, occupies ground once used by Revolutionary War spies

### Medallion's Performance

- **Medallion fund** (flagship of Renaissance): ~**40% annual returns** over three decades — "by a wide margin unmatched in the investing world"
- For comparison: **Warren Buffett's Berkshire Hathaway** averaged ~20% annually (though Berkshire = $150B AUM vs. Medallion's $5B)
- When Medallion posted a rare **0.5% loss in a single quarter of 1999**, at least one employee actually wept
- Many in "quantdom" wonder whether Medallion possesses **the Truth** — the holy grail of market prediction

### James Simons: Origins

- **James Harris Simons** grew up near Boston; as a toddler puzzled over **Zeno's paradox** after learning a car could run out of gas (if always losing half, why does it ever reach zero?)
- 1955: enrolled at **MIT**, caught poker bug, cruised through bachelor's in 3 years, master's in 1
- PhD at Berkeley studying physics; first taste of commodities trading — made money on soybeans
- Post-doctorate: taught at MIT and Harvard; dissatisfied with professor's salary, joined the **Institute for Defense Analysis (IDA)** — a nonprofit Defense Dept. research wing, Cold War code-breaking haven at Princeton
- 1967: **Vietnam War** opposition — Simons wrote a letter to *New York Times Magazine* contradicting IDA president **Maxwell Taylor** (former Joint Chiefs chairman) who had written a pro-war article

> "The only available course consistent with a rational defense policy is to withdraw with the greatest possible dispatch." — *James Simons, NYT Magazine letter, October 1967*

- The letter cost Simons his job at IDA
- 1968: became chairman of the **math department at SUNY Stony Brook** (Long Island, just up the road from Setauket); built it into a mecca for math prodigies
- 1977: left Stony Brook after winning the **Oswald Veblen Prize** (one of geometry's highest honors, awarded every 5 years by the American Mathematics Society)
- With **Shiing-Shen Chern**, developed **Chern-Simons theory** — a key component of string theory

### Building Monometrics and Axcom

- Simons started **Monometrics** in a strip mall near the East Setauket train station
- Recruited **Lenny Baum**, IDA cryptanalyst who'd done work on automated speech recognition
- **Baum-Welch algorithm**: Baum and **Lloyd Welch** designed it to find patterns in **hidden Markov processes** — proved to be a powerful code-breaking tool with financial applications
- **Markov process** (named after Russian mathematician **Andrey Markov**): sequence of events where each outcome depends on current state but not history — a random walk with contingent variables (e.g., Monopoly dice rolls)
- **Hidden Markov process**: underlying random sequence with unknown parameters — you observe signals (exclamations during a phone call about a Monopoly game) and infer the hidden state; with enough data, Baum-Welch can predict what comes next

> "Why should I do this? Will I live longer?" — *Lenny Baum, skeptical about investing*
> "Because you'll know you lived." — *Jim Simons's reply*

- Baum turned out to be a brilliant **fundamental trader** (currencies, commodities based on macro/policy analysis), not the quant Simons envisioned
- Simons brought in **James Ax**, a Bronx-born math professor from Stony Brook, to build model-driven trading
- Mid-1980s: Simons and Ax spun out **Axcom Ltd.** from Monometrics; Ax moved to **Huntington Beach, CA**
- Axcom was the trading advisor for the fund owned by **Renaissance Technologies** (founded July 1982)
- Added game theory expert **Elwyn Berlekamp** (Berkeley) — had worked with **Claude Shannon** and **John Kelly** at MIT; briefly met Simons at IDA in the 1960s

### Medallion's Near-Death and Turnaround

- Fund renamed **Medallion** in 1988 in honor of math prizes Ax and Simons had both won
- Almost immediately, performance collapsed: second half of 1988 losses piled up; by April 1989, **down ~30%**
- Simons ordered Ax to stop trading; Ax refused and hired a lawyer threatening to sue
- **Elwyn Berlekamp** returned from a trip to Egypt, bought out Ax's two-thirds stake, moved HQ to **Berkeley** (9th floor of Shattuck Avenue building)
- **Crucial fix: shift to higher-frequency trading**
  - Previous approach: hold positions days to weeks
  - New approach: shorten holding periods to less than a day, sometimes just an hour
  - Rationale: statistically, near-term prediction (tomorrow, next hour) is far more reliable than predicting a week out
- Berlekamp's analogy: **blackjack** — edge is small, but law of large numbers works in your favor if you play thousands of hands. The goal is to make as many bets as possible as long as there's a slight statistical edge
- By November 1989, Medallion was back; **gained 55% after fees in 1990**
- 1993: Simons closed fund to new investors with **$280M in assets** (models couldn't handle more capital)
- 1994: returns hit **71%**
- The success became so reliable that Ph.D.-sporting staff forgot what it was like to lose

### Renaissance's Hiring Strategy: Speech Recognition as the Key

- Early 1990s: Renaissance hired specialists from **IBM's Thomas J. Watson Research Center** speech recognition group:
  - **Peter Brown** and **Robert Mercer** (November 1993) — co-founders of IBM's speech recognition group
  - Later: **Lalit Bahl**, brothers **Vincent and Stephen Della Pietra**
- Brown: freakishly hard worker, slept on Murphy bed at HQ, deduced squash was the most efficient exercise — solved math conundrums and wired advanced computers
- Mercer: known as the "big gun" — "just aim Bob at it and fire"
- Brown and Mercer were eventually named **co-CEOs of Renaissance** after Simons stepped down in late 2009

### The Speech Recognition / Finance Connection

- Connection between speech recognition and trading:
  - Speech recognition: computer models use historical acoustic data + probability functions to predict what sound comes next, continuously updating
  - Financial data: also strings of data — by applying speech recognition models to price series (e.g., soybean prices), you can estimate a range of probabilities for future price direction
- The connection runs through **information theory** — which itself grew out of WWII code-breaking efforts
- Common thread across all Renaissance talent: cryptographers trained to find **hidden messages in seemingly random strings** — applied to tick-by-tick price data, cross-asset relationships (oil vs. dollar vs. gold)

> "It's a statistical game. You discern phenomena in the market. Are they for real? That's the key question. You must make sure it's not model error or just noise." — *Nick Patterson, former Renaissance analyst/cryptographer*

> "Our edge was quite small, but it's like being the house player at a casino. You have a small edge on every bet, and you have to know how to handle that." — *Nick Patterson*

### Simons on Market Patterns

> "Patterns of price movements are not random. However, they're close enough to random so that getting some excess, some edge out of it, is not easy and not so obvious, thank God." — *Jim Simons*

> "God probably doesn't care." — *Jim Simons (follow-up)*

- **Paul Samuelson** (MIT economist, Nobel laureate) visited Renaissance in 2003 — he'd long held markets were unbeatable, but qualified: if anyone could do it, they'd hide away and not tell anyone
  - "Well, it looks like I've found you," Samuelson told the assembled quants

### Simons's Paranoia and Renaissance Culture

- Medallion models tweaked far more frequently than other quant funds — adjusts for market conditions constantly based on complex signals; faster trading = more flexibility to shift focus
- **Simons's maxim**: "The wolf is at the door" — employees throughout the 1990s expected the run to end any quarter
- 2003: Renaissance sued former employees **Alexander Belopolsky** and **Pavel Volfbeyn** (MIT physicists) who'd left for **Millennium Partners** — accused of misappropriating trade secrets
  - Volfbeyn counter-accused Renaissance of asking him to hack **POSIT** (dark pool electronic market); case settled, but message to employees was clear
- March 2006: **Alexander Astashkevich**, a 37-year-old MIT grad at Renaissance, shot and killed his estranged wife in Port Jefferson, Long Island, then turned the gun on himself
- **Robert Frey** left Renaissance in 2004 partly because he couldn't handle the gut-wrenching daily volatility — even Medallion's wins felt ephemeral

---

## Chapter 7: The Money Grid

### The Money Grid Defined

- Late 1990s: quants collectively building a massive electronic financial network — the **Money Grid**
  - **Ken Griffin**: convertible bonds, Chicago
  - **Jim Simons**: Medallion, East Setauket
  - **Boaz Weinstein**: derivatives at Deutsche Bank
  - **Peter Muller**: stock trading at Morgan Stanley
  - **Cliff Asness**: value/momentum at AQR
- Key architects of the Money Grid: **Ed Thorp**, **Fischer Black**, **Robert Merton**, **Barr Rosenberg**
- **Michael Bloomberg** (former Salomon Brothers trader): designed the Bloomberg terminal — instant data on any security worldwide, turned him into a billionaire
- **Nasdaq**: all-electronic transactions vs. NYSE's floor-based human system → cheaper, faster global stock trading
- Money turned digital — a push-button electronic matrix of "unfathomable complexity"

### Ken Griffin / Citadel

- **Citadel Investment Group** launched November 1, 1990, with **$4.6 million** in capital
  - Year 1: **+43%**; Year 2: **+41%**; Year 3: **+24%**
- Early specialty: convertible bond arbitrage using mathematical models to find mispriced bonds
- Landmark early trade — **ADT Security Services** convertible bond:
  - Bond traded at discount because converting to stock meant missing next dividend
  - Griffin discovered: in the UK, the dividend was a "scrip issue" — meaning UK buyers *would* receive it
  - Bond was therefore underpriced; Citadel bought as many as possible; trade put Citadel on the map
- By mid-twenties, Griffin managing nearly **$200M** with 60 employees in a 3,000 sq. ft. Chicago Loop office
- 1994 crisis: **Alan Greenspan** surprise rate hike devastated convertible bond market; Citadel dropped **4.3%**, AUM fell to $120M — only year before 2008 that flagship **Kensington fund** lost money
- Response: instituted **multi-year investor lockups** (rolling 2-year terms) — so panicked investors couldn't force liquidation at worst moments. Model locked in by July 1998 — just in time for LTCM crisis
- LTCM collapse 1998: Citadel bought distressed assets while others sold; Kensington gained **31%**; AUM exceeded $1B

### Citadel's Diversification

- Evolved into a full **multistrategy fund**:
  - Convertible bonds, Japanese warrants (early 1990s)
  - 1994: **merger arbitrage** group
  - 1994: **stat arb fund** (inspired by Thorp's Ridgeline Partners)
  - 1999: **mortgage-backed securities**
  - Energy trading after **Enron's collapse** (December 2001 — Griffin flew to recruit energy traders within a day of bankruptcy filing, hired meteorologists to track supply/demand)
  - Also launched reinsurance, internal **market-making operation**
- By early 2000s: $6B AUM, one of world's six largest hedge funds
- Returns: **+25% (1998), +40% (1999), +46% (2000), +19% (2001)** — made money through dot-com crash

### Griffin's Wealth and Lifestyle

- Youngest self-made member of **Forbes 400** in 2002; #10 on *Fortune*'s richest under-40 in 2003 (~$725M net worth)
- Art: paid **$60.5M for Cézanne's *Curtain Jug and Fruit Bowl*** (1999); acquired Degas *Little Dancer, Aged 14* and *Green Dancer*
- 2003 wedding: held at the **Palace of Versailles** — Cirque du Soleil performed, Donna Summer sang, guests dangled from helium balloons; reception at Hameau de la Reine (Marie Antoinette's faux peasant village)
- Top lieutenants who later departed:
  - **Alec Litowitz** (merger arb desk) → launched **Magnetar Capital** ($2B, 2005) — became notorious for its role in the subprime/CDO crisis
  - **David Bunning** (global credit)

### Peter Muller / PDT at Morgan Stanley (Beginning)

- 1991: Muller launched quantitative trading at Morgan Stanley using BARRA models — immediate disaster
  - Models were theoretically brilliant but execution was too slow, trading costs were lethal, program bugs corrupted orders
- Set up on 33rd floor of Morgan's Exxon Building (1251 Avenue of the Americas) — same building as Bamberger and Tartaglia's earlier stat-arb experiment
- First hire: **Kim Elsesser**, MIT operations research programmer

<!-- pp. 141-160 -->

## Chapter (PDT continued): Midas Ascending

### PDT's Dream Team (1994)

- **Peter Muller** named the group **Process Driven Trading (PDT)** — "process-driven"
  was shorthand for complex math algorithms only a few thousand people understood
- **Amy Elsesser** co-built PDT from scratch; wrote trading models in C, hooked
  Unix workstations to Morgan's mainframe, began trading US, Japan, London, Paris
- 1993: Muller visited **Prediction Company** in Santa Fe — a cutting-edge
  computerized trading firm seeking seed capital from Wall Street
  - Founded by **Doyne Farmer**, chaos theory physicist who (like Thorp) had
    built roulette-predicting computers in "magic" shoes before moving to markets
  - Muller played poker at the meeting — extracted info, gave nothing back
  - Farmer eventually kicked him out: "Pete didn't give us anything"

### Survival Pitch to John Mack

- Morgan management targeted PDT for cuts; **John Mack** (newly named president)
  called a survival meeting
- Muller's strategy: oiled hair, suit, total calm — *Stay calm, look cool, be confident*
- Flatly admitted PDT hadn't succeeded yet — but computerized trading was the future
- Mack gave a confident nod. PDT survived.

### The Dream Team (Early 1994)

- **Mike Reed** — geophysicist, Ph.D. electrical engineering, Princeton
- **Ken Nickerson** — brooding math expert, Ph.D. operations research, Stanford
- **Shakil Ahmed** — computer programming whiz, Princeton
- **Amy Wong** — master's electrical engineering, MIT
- Advantage of being inside a bank: hedge funds had to route trades *through*
  Morgan as broker — PDT could see their flow. One such client: **Renaissance
  Technologies' Nova fund**, run by **Robert Frey** (former Tartaglia protégé)
  - Mid-1990s: Nova had a bad stretch; PDT absorbed the positions, profited,
    and got a rare glimpse inside Renaissance's architecture

### Robot Midas

- PDT built **Midas** — an automated trading machine ("a robot for making money")
- Strategy: **statistical arbitrage** — same as Bamberger/Tartaglia's 1980s invention
- Midas focused on sector pairs: oil drillers (Exxon/Chevron), airlines
  (American/United) — if 4 airlines up and 3 down, short the up, buy the down
- By Q4 1994, money was piling up: trades "popped off like firecrackers"
- Elsesser once heard a radio report of "unusual trading activity wreaking havoc
  in Tokyo markets" and panicked — *Could that be us? Shit.* — rushed back to office.
  PDT wasn't responsible, but the fear was ever-present: the machine could
  unleash tsunamis of orders like a "computerized Frankenstein"

### PDT vs. Renaissance

- PDT's performance matched — and at times outpaced — Renaissance's **Medallion fund**
- In 1997, Medallion's returns "leapt to a new dimension" — nobody knew how
- Renaissance stopped routing through Morgan, fearing Muller was eyeballing strategies
- Muller grew equally paranoid; PDT traders kept in **silos**, unaware of others' positions

### "Always Trust the Machine"

- Early on, Muller and Elsesser made snap decisions to override models during
  unexpected Fed moves or economic surprises — always turned out to be bad
- Concluded: computers more reliable than humans

> "Always trust the machine" — PDT's mantra

### APT's Warning

- Muller discovered old records from **APT** (Tartaglia's group) — realized PDT
  hadn't invented stat arb, just rediscovered it
- Key lesson from APT's history: huge returns, then music stopped suddenly
- Muller's takeaway: never let your guard down — always keep improving the system

### Jaipal Tuttle and Human Error

- **Jaipal Tuttle** (1995 hire) — Ph.D. physics, UC Santa Cruz; joined after
  Japan's market collapse killed his warrants business in London
- No programming skills → became PDT's **"human trader"**: called in trades
  over the phone for markets not yet fully automated
- Automated trading glitches:
  - PDT once mistakenly sold ~$80 million in stock in 15 minutes due to a bug
  - A consultant crossed his own buy/sell orders on S&P 500 options (tens of millions);
    ran down the hall screaming "Stop! *Stoooppp!* Don't buy, sell, *seeelll!*"
  - Lesson confirmed: humans are flawed; let the computer run the show

### PDT Culture and Expansion

- Moved to **1585 Broadway** (Morgan's new HQ) in 1995 — sixth floor, one above
  the main trading floor
- **Vikram Pandit** (future Citigroup CEO) oversaw PDT: "I want lots of systems"
- PDT expanded into Eurodollar futures, energy futures, bonds, options — anything
  they could model
- Group culture was deliberately anti-Wall Street: tropical trips, ski trips, shared
  salmon rolls at lunch — "flower children on the trading floor"
- Extremely low turnover in an industry known for churn

### PDT's Eccentric Characters

- One quant duct-taped a cardboard canopy over his monitor to block glare;
  a Morgan bigwig across the hall was outraged
- Another taped paper over motion sensors to work in the dark at night
- Muller's interview trick: ask applicants their wallet contents at **95% confidence**
  — correct answer is $0 to several thousand (very wide range). Most got it wrong
  and got angry. Point: humans systematically underestimate uncertainty.
- Muller also interviewed **professional poker players** — colleagues were baffled,
  and none panned out

### PDT's Staggering Profits

- Morgan Stanley won't disclose PDT's exact numbers, but:
  - **10 years through 2006: ~$4 billion in profits** (after Morgan's cut)
  - PDT members took home roughly **$1 billion** over that period
  - In peak years, Muller/Nickerson/Ahmed earned more than Morgan Stanley's CEO
  - **In late 1990s–early 2000s, PDT accounted for one-quarter of Morgan Stanley's net income**
- By 1999, Midas alone had delivered **$1 billion in net income** in 5 years

> "PDT keeps the lights running at Morgan Stanley." — **Vikram Pandit**

> "I would describe it as a superhumanly large amount... It was an exceptionally
> well-functioning machine." — **Jaipal Tuttle**

---

## Asness Section: Goldman's Quantitative Research Group

### Asness Arrives at Goldman (Late 1994)

- **Cliff Asness** took a full-time job at Goldman in late 1994 with a broad mandate:
  build quant models to forecast returns across multiple asset classes
- Goldman had bet on book-smarts since **Fischer Black** in the 1980s; by early
  1990s it was the go-to bank for "mathletes"
- Asness named his operation the **Quantitative Research Group (QRG)**

### QRG's Team

- Recruited University of Chicago all-stars:
  - **Ross Stevens**, **Robert Krail**, **Brian Hurst**, **John Liew**
  - Krail and Liew had worked at **Trout Trading** (founded by **Monroe Trout Jr.**)
    building quant models — Liew had planned an academic career until trading proved fun

> "Don't think of this as a job." — **Robert Krail** to Liew

### Value and Momentum Applied to Countries

- Initial task: help fundamental stock pickers assess opportunities country-by-country
- Key insight: **value and momentum anomalies** that worked for individual stocks
  also work for entire countries
- Method: divide a country's total stock market cap by sum of book values of all
  companies → **country-level price-to-book ratio**
  - Japan P/B = 1.0, France P/B = 2.0 → Japan cheap → long Japan, short France
- Fundamentals of a country's politics or leadership were largely irrelevant from
  a quant desk — same as company management for stock stat arb
- QRG quickly designed models for cheap-vs-expensive opportunities globally;
  momentum strategies followed

### Global Alpha Born (1995)

- Goldman seeded a small internal hedge fund with **$10 million** in 1995
- Named **Global Alpha** — would become one of Wall Street's elite trading operations
- Also would become a **primary catalyst for the quant meltdown of August 2007**
- First year: up **93%**; second year: up **35%** — after losing money for first 8 days
- By late 1997: QRG managing **$5 billion** in long-only portfolio + **~$1 billion** in
  Global Alpha; new hires included **Ray Iwanowski** and **Mark Carhart**
  (Chicago Ph.D. program alums)

### Fischer Black at Goldman

- **Fischer Black** — co-creator of **Black-Scholes** options pricing model with
  **Myron Scholes** and **Robert Merton** (with input from Thorp)
- Contradictions: central figure in quant finance who never took a finance course;
  trained mathematician/astrophysicist; believed in efficient markets but watched
  traders exploit inefficiencies daily
- Quirks: soaked cereal in orange juice, ate only broiled fish + butterless potato
  for lunch, scanned workplaces with a radiation meter, bought long keyboard cords
  to distance from monitor (cancer fears)
- Career path: grew up in Bronxville NY, Harvard, management consulting at
  **Arthur D. Little**, then academia (U. of Chicago → MIT)
- Met **Myron Scholes** in fall 1968; together (with Merton) solved option pricing;
  published groundbreaking research on stock option pricing
- Recruited to Goldman by **Robert Merton** suggestion to **Robert Rubin** (then head
  of Goldman equities, later Clinton Treasury secretary)
- Upon arrival at Goldman's trading floor: "So you're Fischer Black. You don't
  know shit about options." — head of trading, greeting the legend
- Black's job: turn quantitative theories into cash. Lost $500K in his first trade.
  Watching Goldman traders exploit endless inefficiencies, he abandoned pure
  efficient-market orthodoxy
- Saw Goldman's edge as **"the powerful mix of financial theory and computer technology"**
- Asness found Black's **"conversational sinkholes"** — long silences — unnerving

> "It was like the air coming out of the *Hindenburg*." — **Cliff Asness** on
> Black's silences

### Asness's Luck Thesis

- Asness's unusual conviction: **luck** is a major factor in his success
- Global Alpha lost money for 8 straight days at launch, then never looked back
  for a long time — luck changed the trajectory
- In retrospect, the early 1990s–mid-1990s were unusually favorable for both
  value and momentum strategies — Asness and team were in the right place
  at the right time

### The Henry Paulson Meeting

- To reward Asness's group, Goldman arranged a meeting with COO **Henry Paulson**
  (later Goldman CEO, then Bush Treasury secretary)
- Paulson interrupted Asness's presentation: "How many countries are in the EAFE index?"
- Asness said twenty-one. "Name 'em." Paulson had been counting silently — came up
  three short. Asness left humiliated.

### AQR Is Born

- By 1997, Asness restless — Goldman shuttled him around the world, too much
  office politics, not enough research time
- Met **David Kabiller** — Goldman generalist who'd worked fixed income, equities,
  pension services; served as liaison between institutional investors and GSAM
- Kabiller watched Global Alpha's live P&L ticking up by **millions of dollars every second**
- Group began meeting at **Rungsit**, a Thai restaurant on Manhattan's East Side,
  debating whether to leave Goldman
- Settled on a name for the new firm: **Applied Quantitative Research Capital
  Management** — **AQR** for short
- Asness got cold feet; Goldman's bigwigs pressed him to stay; Kabiller was crushed
- Then, late 1997: Kabiller gets a personal phone call from Asness — a man who
  never made personal calls. Something was up.

<!-- pp. 161-180 -->

## Chapter 7 (cont.): The Wolf of Wall Street — AQR Launch & Weinstein Rise

### AQR Capital: Launch

- December 1997: **Cliff Asness**, **Robert Krail**, **David Kabiller**, and **John Liew**
  resigned from Goldman simultaneously; Asness listened to *Les Misérables*
  soundtrack to psych himself up
- August 3, 1998: **AQR Capital** launched with **$1 billion** in start-up capital —
  one of the largest hedge fund launches on record, 3x their original projection
- Turned down **>$1 billion in additional capital** — worried strategies couldn't
  handle so much money
- French fund-of-funds manager **Arpad "Arki" Busson** (beau of Elle Macpherson/
  Uma Thurman) offered his Swiss chalet in exchange for capacity — AQR declined
- Described as a "dream-team blend of Long-Term Capital Management and
  Julian Robertson's Tiger Management"
- AQR gained slightly in its first month, then "fell off a cliff" — the 1998
  Russia/LTCM crisis hit immediately after launch

---

## Weinstein Section

### Boaz Weinstein: Early Culture

- Fall 2003: **Boaz Weinstein**'s **Deutsche Bank** credit traders held a Las Vegas
  offsite — blackjack, poker, roulette, then paintball
- **"Prop" traders** (gunslingers betting bank capital) vs. **"flow" traders**
  (client go-betweens) faced off in paintball; prop traders won
- Deutsche Bank had just been named **Derivatives House of the Year** by *Risk*
  magazine, displacing J.P. Morgan ("enemy number one")

> "At Deutsche Bank, risk wasn't fucking *managed*. Risk was bitch-slapped, risk
> was tamed and told what to do." — Patterson's characterization of the culture

- Weinstein's childhood dream: elite Wall Street trader, nurtured watching
  **Louis Rukeyser** on TV as a chess prodigy on the Upper East Side

### Weinstein's Rise at Deutsche Bank

- 1998: Joined Deutsche Bank's **credit derivatives desk** at age 24 — nervous
  at first, but absorbed knowledge rapidly with a photographic memory
- Background: trading **floating rate notes** (variable-rate bonds); natural
  bridge to **credit default swaps (CDS)**
- **Ron Tanemura** explained CDS to Weinstein: essentially a way to short a
  loan or bond — buying protection = short position on credit
- CDS was so new that few banks traded it heavily; Weinstein made road trips
  to firms like **BlackRock** to evangelize the instrument
- 1998: Was **shorting the credit market** via CDS when Russia defaulted and
  LTCIM collapsed — made a large profit for Deutsche Bank
- 1999: Promoted to **vice president**
- 2001: Named **managing director** at age 27 — one of the youngest in
  Deutsche Bank's history

### Regulatory Tailwind

- November 1999: **Glass-Steagall Act of 1933** repealed — removed the wall
  between investment banking and commercial banking; prop desks gained access
  to deposit-side capital
- December 2000: Congress passed legislation **exempting derivatives from
  intense federal scrutiny** — cleared the way for the 2000s derivatives boom

### CDS Market Stress Tests

- 2000 **California utilities crisis** — first real test; credit market functioned
- Late 2001: **Enron collapse** — proved CDS market could withstand a major
  corporate default
- **WorldCom/telecom meltdown** — another trial by fire; CDS market passed
- These events validated the market and set the stage for explosive growth

### AOL Time Warner Trade (2002)

- By 2002 recession, investors panicked over **AOL Time Warner** debt even
  though stock was only down ~20%
- Weinstein noticed bond prices implied near-bankruptcy for a company with
  **CNN and HBO** — fundamentally wrong
- Trade: **bought AOL bonds + shorted the stock** to hedge
- Result: huge win as bond market and company recovered

### Gambling Culture

- First hire **Bing Wang** — finished 34th in the 2005 World Series of Poker
- Several Deutsche traders were members of **MIT's blackjack team**
- Weinstein card-counted at Vegas casinos using techniques from **Ed Thorp**'s
  *Beat the Dealer*; reportedly banned from more than one casino
- Weekly **$100 buy-in poker game** on Deutsche's trading floor every Friday
- Deutsche's senior management was London/Frankfurt-based, leaving Weinstein
  effectively unsupervised at **60 Wall Street** — "cowboy capitalism"

### Joining the Quant Poker Circle

- 2004: Weinstein attended **Wall Street Poker Night** at St. Regis Hotel;
  met **Neil Chriss** (then at SAC Capital), **Peter Muller**, **Cliff Asness**
- Entry bar: losing tens of thousands couldn't matter financially — **8-figure
  net worth minimum** to qualify
- Weinstein proved himself and became a **permanent member** of the inner circle
- 2005: Weinstein's boss **Anshu Jain** met Warren Buffett in Omaha; Buffett
  invited Weinstein to a NetJets poker tournament in Las Vegas
- Weinstein won the tournament's grand prize: **a new Maserati**

### Capital Structure Arbitrage — Signature Strategy

- Core trade: exploit **mispricing between a company's debt and equity**
- If bonds undervalued vs. stock → go long bonds, short stock; wait for
  convergence
- Used CDS creatively to arb the inefficiency — "the old relative-value
  arbitrage trade, much like that crafted by **Ed Thorp** in the 1960s,
  wrapped in fancy new derivative clothes"
- Was building a diversified multistrategy fund modeled on **Ken Griffin**'s
  Citadel approach

### GM Trade Disaster and Recovery (2005)

- Weinstein entered a capital structure arb on **General Motors**: GM stock
  had fallen ~$25-30, debt crushed to near-bankruptcy levels
- Thesis: even in bankruptcy, debt holders would get **≥40¢ on the dollar**;
  stock would be worthless → sell CDS protection on GM debt + short GM stock
- May 2005: **Kirk Kerkorian** made a surprise tender offer for 28 million GM
  shares via **Tracinda Corp.** → stock surged, crushing the short
- Days later: **S&P and Moody's downgraded GM debt to junk** → forced selling
  drove debt down further
- Both legs of the trade moved against him simultaneously — the opposite of
  what the model predicted

> *The market is irrational, and Kerkorian is nuts. Eventually things will move
> back into line. The Truth will be restored.* — Weinstein's internal monologue

- Internal debate: **Bing Wang** argued "Load the boat" (double down);
  others said cut the loss
- Weinstein initially played it safe, then gradually added to the position
- By end of 2005 and into 2006: **GM trade paid off** — stock fell, debt
  recovered after the rating downgrade panic subsided
- Lesson: arbitrage trades can spin out of control from random outside events,
  but if you can hold long enough, the Truth reasserts itself — **"or so he
  thought"**

---

## Chapter 8: Living the Dream

### Hedge Fund Boom (Early 2000s)

- Pension funds and endowments flooding into hedge funds; banks expanding
  prop desks: **Global Alpha** (Goldman), **PDT** (Morgan Stanley),
  Weinstein's credit shop (Deutsche Bank)
- **Ed Thorp** saw the explosion as a dark omen — too much money chasing the
  same strategies, copycat crowding
- October 2002: Thorp shut down his stat arb fund, **Ridgeline Partners**

### Griffin: Citadel Becomes a Machine

- **Ken Griffin**'s **Citadel Investment Group** became one of the most
  technologically advanced trading operations on the Street
- Infrastructure details: offices in Chicago, SF, NY, London, Tokyo, Hong Kong;
  **1,000+ employees**; own rooftop generator; oxygen-draining fire suppression
  in server room; secret backup data center in **Downers Grove, IL**; every
  PC networked into a distributed "cloud" computer crunching mortgage positions
- 2003: Hired Russian math genius **Misha Malyshev** for a secretive stat arb
  project — launched as **Tactical Trading** on July 25, 2004; posted consistent
  gains with very low volatility, focused on speed
- Hired **Matthew Andresen** (creator of electronic trading platform Island ECN)
  to build options market-making business → **Citadel Derivatives Group Investors**,
  eventually the **largest listed options dealer in the world**
- Assets neared **$15 billion**

### Griffin's Enemies

- Citadel was aggressively poaching talent from other funds
- **Daniel Loeb** (Third Point Partners) sent a scathing email after Citadel
  hired **Andrew Rechtschaffen** from **David Einhorn**'s Greenlight Capital:

> "I find the disconnect between your self-proclaimed 'good to great, Jim
> Collins–esque' organization and the reality of the gulag you created quite
> laughable. You are surrounded by sycophants, but even you must know that
> the people who work for you despise and resent you." — Daniel Loeb to Griffin

- Loeb's accusations had truth: **high turnover**, intense pressure, bitter
  departures; departures were often dripping with bad blood
- Returns had also slipped: Kensington Fund +13% in 2002, then <10% annually
  for three years — attributed to strategy crowding (the same problem that
  pushed Thorp out)
- Culture contrast: Griffin threw lavish parties, rented AMC River 24 for
  private screenings of *The Dark Knight*, *Star Wars Episode III* — employees
  left bitter but also rich

### Systemic Risk Concerns

- Dresdner Kleinwort researchers warned Citadel's leverage could destabilize
  markets: "the balance sheet of today's Citadel hedge fund looks quite
  similar to LTCM"
- Citadel's leverage ~**8 to 1** (some estimates 16:1) vs. LTCM's 30:1
  (topped 100:1 in 1998 meltdown) — different scale but growing fast

### Amaranth Collapse (September 2006) — Griffin's Coup

- **Amaranth Advisors** ($10 billion fund) imploded after Canadian energy
  trader **Brian Hunter** lost **$5 billion in one week** betting on natural
  gas — largest hedge fund blowup ever, exceeding LTCM
- Hunter worked from Calgary in a gray Ferrari; had a reputation for doubling
  down on losing trades
- Trigger: **Hurricane Katrina** volatility in natural gas; storage glut reports
  tanked prices; Hunter boosted positions as losses mounted
- Griffin smelled opportunity: Citadel's energy experts (including Enron alumni)
  pored over Amaranth's books; Griffin called COO **Charlie Winkler**
- Deal: **Citadel took half of Amaranth's energy book; JP Morgan took the other
  half** — critics said it was stupid; Citadel gained **30%** that year
- The move compared to Warren Buffett-style distressed opportunism; Griffin
  joined the "speed-dial list" of last-resort buyers

### The Gilded Age Peak

- Griffin bought **Jasper Johns' *False Start*** for **$80 million** (Oct 2006)
  — most expensive painting by a living artist ever sold; seller was David Geffen
- Donated **$19 million** to Art Institute of Chicago; Citadel garage held
  ~**6 Ferraris**, each monitored on trading floor screens
- Griffin's stated goal: turn Citadel into **"the next Goldman Sachs"** — an
  "enduring financial institution"
- Citadel sold **$2 billion of high-grade bonds** in late 2006 — first hedge
  fund to raise on bond market; widely seen as IPO groundwork

### Fortress and Blackstone IPOs (Early 2007)

- **Fortress Investment Group** IPO'd February 2007 at $18.50/share; stock
  hit $35 on day one, closed at $31; five founders cleared **>$10 billion**
- **Stephen Schwarzman** (Blackstone Group) threw a lavish 60th birthday party
  at the Seventh Regiment Armory on Park Avenue — Colin Powell, Michael
  Bloomberg, Donald Trump attended; Rod Stewart performed; *Fortune* named
  him "Wall Street's Man of the Moment"
- Blackstone had just completed a **$39 billion leveraged buyout of Equity
  Office Properties** — largest LBO in history
- Blackstone raised **$4.6 billion** in its June 2007 IPO; Schwarzman personally
  pocketed ~**$1 billion**; his stake valued at **$7.8 billion**
- Patterson frames Schwarzman's party as **the crest of the boom** — "few knew
  it at the time"

### Sowood Capital Collapse (July 2007) — First Crack

- **Sowood Capital Management** ($3 billion, Boston): run by **Jeffrey Larson**,
  former Harvard endowment star
- Early 2007: Larson shorted junior debt (first-loss tranches), hedged with
  higher-grade debt, then leveraged the whole book to **12:1**
- June 2007: Moody's downgraded $5 billion of subprime mortgage bonds;
  July 10: S&P warned it might downgrade $12 billion more (including bonds
  from **New Century Financial**, already bankrupt)
- Other hedge funds with similar bets dumped everything → **credit markets
  gummed up**; nobody wanted to buy even Sowood's "safe" high-grade bonds

> "S&P's actions are going to force a lot more people to come to Jesus. This
> could be one of the triggers we've been waiting for." — Christopher Whalen,
> Institutional Risk Analytics

- Larson added leverage as losses mounted; put in **$5.7 million of his own
  cash**; appealed to Harvard endowment for more capital — **Harvard declined**
- July 27 (Friday): Sowood down **10%**; by end of the weekend... [continues]
- Sowood's collapse: first concrete signal of the great unwinding that would
  nearly destroy the global financial system

<!-- pp. 181-200 -->

## Griffin / Citadel — Sowood Acquisition (cont.)

- **Sowood Capital** was down 40% when founder **Jeff Larson** called **Ken Griffin** to bail him out
- Griffin, vacationing in France, mobilized 30 Citadel traders to comb Sowood's books over a weekend
- Citadel purchased most of Sowood's remaining positions for **$1.4 billion** — more than half of what the fund had been worth months earlier
- Griffin had told clients markets were acting irrationally and a rebound was imminent; Sowood fit his thesis perfectly
- By August 2007, Citadel had **$15.8 billion** in assets, up from $4.6 million when Griffin started in 1990
- Foreshadowing: "Little did he realize that a year later, Citadel itself would be teetering on the edge of collapse"

