## Peter Muller — Life Between Trading

### The Wandering Quant
- **PDT** (Process Driven Trading) was churning out hundreds of millions yearly for **Morgan Stanley** by early 2000s
- PDT commanded the **largest proprietary trading book** in Morgan Stanley's equities division
- PDT traders broke dress code — ripped jeans, T-shirts, tennis shoes among bespoke-suited bankers
  - PDT nerds made 10x the bonus of traditional bankers who passed them in the elevators
- Muller kept PDT so secret that few Morgan employees knew the group existed — paranoid about strategy copying

### Muller's Lifestyle (Late 1990s–2000s)
- Hiking (Kalalau Trail, Kauai — 11 miles, ancient path, completed entire trail in one day with friends)
- **Heli-skiing** at Jackson Hole, kayaking New Zealand, river trips Arizona/Idaho
- In 2004, self-produced album *More Than This* — sentimental ballads, press release said he "could no longer find happiness in the corporate world"
- Hosted "songwriters' circle" Tuesday nights at his Tribeca apartment; maintained personal website
- Performed as subway busker playing **Harry Chapin's "Cat's in the Cradle"** — colleagues from Morgan did double-takes
- Attended derivatives conference in Barcelona (with **Myron Scholes** of LTCM), then busked on La Rambla — his first time singing in public

### Personal Turmoil
- Girlfriend Katie (catalog designer, introduced by Elsesser) left him for a mutual friend — Muller became an emotional wreck, weeping at his desk
- Threw himself into music; distributed heartbreak songs around Morgan Stanley's trading floor
  - Song "Plug and Play Girl" — PDT colleagues were mortified
- One PDT trader coined "**seagull management**" for Muller's style: swoop in occasionally, critique everything, vanish

### Stepping Back from PDT
- Around 2000, **Shakil Ahmed** took over day-to-day operations; Muller became paid advisor/partner
- By early-to-mid 2000s, Muller was performing at Greenwich Village cabarets (the Cutting Room, Makor Cafe)
- Won **$98,000** on World Poker Tour in 2004; beat **Cliff Asness** in the Wall Street Poker Night final (March 2006)
- Monthly quant poker games: Muller, **Weinstein**, **Asness**, **Chriss** — $10,000 buy-in, pots much higher
  - Asness: too competitive, hated folding small losses; Muller: ice-cold, mastered when to fold/raise/go all-in

### Muller Returns to PDT (2006–2007)
- PDT posted only single-digit gains in 2006 as **stat arb copycats** flooded in; Morgan's higher-ups wanted more
- Muller announced he wanted back in — power struggle ensued; Shakil Ahmed quit, moved to **Citigroup** under **Vikram Pandit**
- Muller expanded PDT's **quant fundamental book** — longer-term value/momentum trades (weeks to months vs. Midas trades lasting a day)
  - Book grew from ~$2 billion to $5+ billion; "They basically turned a large part of PDT into AQR"
- **Ken Griffin** (running similar strategies) overheard telling Muller he was "sorry to hear he'd come back" — a double-edged dig

> "He wouldn't have much time to enjoy himself. Just months after he returned, Muller would face the biggest test of his career: a brutal meltdown that nearly destroyed PDT."

