## Nassim Nicholas Taleb — The Anti-Quant

### Background & The Black Monday Origin Story
- Met Muller and other quants at **Neil Chriss's** 2002 wedding at Trout-beck resort (Berkshire foothills)
- Born 1960, Amioun, Lebanon — experienced extreme randomness firsthand during the 15-year Lebanese civil war
- Left Lebanon for **University of Paris** (math/economics), then **Wharton** (MBA)
- At **First Boston** age 28: accumulated large position in **out-of-the-money Eurodollar futures**
- **Black Monday (Oct 19, 1987)**: panicking investors fled into liquid assets including Eurodollars — Taleb's position exploded, netting ~**$40 million in one day**
- Critical self-awareness: "He was well aware that the gains had nothing to do with why he'd been investing in Eurodollars. He'd been very, very lucky, and he knew it."
- Later: Ph.D. from **University of Paris Dauphine**, textbook on option trading, pit trader at **Chicago Mercantile Exchange**
- 1999: started teaching at NYU and launched hedge fund **Empirica** (named for empirical knowledge)

### Taleb vs. Quant Models
- Argued that no model — not even those incorporating **Mandelbrot's Lévy fat-tailed processes** — could capture the true extremity of market volatility
- Referenced models: **"jump diffusion"** (allows sudden price leaps), **GARCH** (generalized autoregressive conditional heteroscedasticity — accounts for immediate past, allows fat-tailed feedback)
- Core thesis: markets make moves far more extreme than any model can factor in; you will be wiped out

### The Wedding Table Confrontation (2002)
- Taleb vs. Muller at Chriss's reception: grew heated, Taleb pounding the table
- > "It is impossible. You will be wiped out, I swear it!" — Taleb shouting at Muller
- > "There is no free lunch. If ten thousand people flip a coin, after ten flips the odds are there will be someone who has turned up heads every time. People will hail this man as a genius... This is exactly what happened to LTCM. But it's obvious that LTCM didn't know shit about risk control. They were all charlatans." — Taleb
- Muller dismissive: PDT could *never* melt down; Taleb didn't know what he was talking about
- Book referenced: **Fooled by Randomness** (Taleb, 2001) — nearly all successful investors are more lucky than skilled

---

## Cliff Asness / AQR — The Dot-Com Near-Death

### AQR's Strategy & the Bubble Problem
- AQR launched August 1998: **long cheap stocks** (low price-to-book), **short expensive stocks**
- 1999 was the worst possible environment — dot-com babies with no earnings surged; cheap value stocks (Bank of America, Ford, GM) stagnated
- AQR lost **35% in first 20 months**; coughed up $600 million of $1 billion seed capital as investors fled
- By early 2000, AQR was on life support — months from shutting its doors

> *"What is wrong with these people? They are so monumentally stupid. Their stupidity is killing me."* — Asness to wife Laurel Fraser

- Asness's wife Laurel (met at Goldman) delivered the key insight: "You want this Goldilocks story of just the right irrationality" — when mistakes are *too* big, the strategy breaks
- Lesson internalized: his **Chicago School** efficient markets training had blinded him to the extremes of human irrationality

### "Bubble Logic" (2000) — The Paper
- Asness wrote **"Bubble Logic: Or, How to Learn to Stop Worrying and Love the Bull"** as a protest against dot-com insanity (title riffs on *Dr. Strangelove*)
- S&P P/E ratio hit **44 in June 2000** — more than double in five years, triple the long-term average
- Key argument: the market-is-different-this-time crowd was right — but in a *bad* way
- Showed stocks beat inflation in every 20-year period since 1926, beat bonds and cash — but only because they were historically **priced reasonably relative to earnings**
- Case study: **Cisco Systems** — mathematically impossible for earnings to justify its valuation; yet "Cisco is on almost every 'must own' recommended list I see. Go figure."
- Flew directly in the face of **Fama's Efficient Market Hypothesis**: Asness argued you *could* identify a bubble in real time
  - "Unless we see 20-year growth for the S&P far, far in excess of anything ever seen for 125 years starting from similar good times, long-term S&P returns become quite ugly."
- Paper was never published — dot-com bubble imploded before he finished it (Nasdaq peaked March 2000 at 5,000+; crashed to 1,114 by October 2002)
- AQR's Absolute Return Fund gained **roughly 180%** in the three years following its 2000 low point

### Why Short-Term Quants Survived the Bubble, AQR Didn't
- Renaissance, D.E. Shaw, PDT sailed through largely unscathed — their **high-frequency** strategies captured short-term price changes, benefited from volatility, could exit quickly
- AQR's positions played out over weeks/months — when models were wrong, pain was prolonged and intense

### AQR's Ascent Post-Bubble
- Post-2000 crash: sophisticated investors, pension funds, and endowments flooded into hedge funds; hedge fund AUM surged from ~$100B to **$2 trillion by early 2007**
- Asness personally earned **$37 million in 2002**, **$50 million in 2003**
- AQR moved from cramped Manhattan offices to **Two Greenwich Plaza** (next to train station)
- Asness bought 12,500 sq ft Greenwich mansion for $9.6 million (2004); later purchased 22-acre estate at **Conyers Farm** for a $30 million mansion project
- By late July 2007, AQR had IPO papers drawn up — essentially a done deal, just needed to mail to the SEC

### The Carry Trade
- Major driver of AQR and quant fund returns post-2000: **carry trade**
- Japan's rates below 1% (fighting deflation) — borrow yen nearly for free, invest in higher-yielding assets (bonds, currencies, commodities, subprime mortgages)
- Australia/New Zealand dollars were popular carry destinations; leverage amplified returns
- By early 2007, ~**$1 trillion** staked on carry trade (per *The Economist*) — especially popular at Goldman's **Global Alpha** fund
- Risk: nearly all participants crowded into identical trades — "liquidity sloshing around" pushing up stocks, gold, real estate, oil simultaneously

