## Glossary (pp. 358+)

- **Arbitrage**: Buying and selling two related securities priced differently, betting
  they will converge. Quants use historical relationships between assets; bets assume
  past performance predicts future — an assumption that isn't always true
- **Black-Scholes option-pricing formula**: Mathematical formula for pricing options;
  assumes future volatility is random and explicitly leaves out the likelihood of large
  swings (**fat tails**) — its core flaw
- **Brownian motion**: Seemingly random motion of particles; mathematically a random
  walk whose average can be predicted via the bell curve / normal distribution. Quants
  use it to model volatility of stocks and bank balance sheets
- **Credit default swap (CDS)**: Insurance contract on a bond; price fluctuates with
  bond riskiness. **Boaz Weinstein** at Deutsche Bank was a pioneer in using CDS as a
  betting instrument
- **Collateralized debt obligation (CDO)**: Bundles of credit-card debt or mortgages
  sliced into risk tranches (AAA to BBB). J. P. Morgan quants created "synthetic" CDOs
  bundling CDS; these plunged in 2007–2008 as mortgage defaults surged
- **Convertible bonds**: Fixed-income security with an option warrant to convert to
  shares. **Ed Thorp** devised a mathematical pricing method for warrants in the 1960s
  that anticipated Black-Scholes
- **Efficient-market hypothesis (EMH)**: All information is instantly priced in; beating
  the market consistently is impossible. Chief proponent: **Eugene Fama** (U of Chicago).
  Ironically, Fama trained many quants who went to Wall Street to beat the market —
  using Fama-derived strategies that blew up in August 2007

<!-- pp. 361-364 -->

## Glossary (continued) & Back Matter

### Fat Tail

- Market volatility typically measured via the **bell curve** (normal distribution),
  representing **Brownian motion** of market movements
- Tails (left and right sides of the curve) slope downward under normal assumptions
- A **fat tail** = a highly unlikely "**black swan**" event not captured by the bell
  curve; visually appears as a bulge on either side
- **Benoit Mandelbrot** first devised methods to describe extreme market events
  in the 1960s — but was largely ignored by the quant establishment

### Gaussian Copula

- Model developed by financial engineer **David X. Li** to predict price correlations
  between slices of **collateralized debt obligations (CDOs)**
- **Copulas**: mathematical functions calculating connections between two variables —
  how they "copulate" (when X happens, there's a Y chance Z happens)
- Li's copulas named after **Carl Friedrich Gauss**, 19th-century German mathematician
  who measured stellar motion via the bell curve
- CDO default-risk correlations were therefore grounded in the bell curve —
  a copula is essentially a **multidimensional bell curve**
- **Fatal flaw**: in the credit crisis beginning August 2007, correlations between
  CDO slices became far tighter than the model predicted — it catastrophically failed

### Hedge Fund

- Investment vehicle open only to wealthy individuals or institutions
  (pension funds, endowments)
- Typically use heavy **leverage** (borrowed money) + charge **2-and-20 fees**
  (2% AUM + 20%+ of profits)
- First hedge fund launched **1949** by **Alfred Winslow Jones** (a reporter) —
  "hedged" by taking offsetting long and short positions in stocks
- **Ed Thorp** launched **Convertible Hedge Associates** in 1969, later renamed
  **Princeton/Newport Partners** — one of the earliest quant hedge funds

### Law of Large Numbers

- The more observations made, the greater the certainty of prediction
- Example: 10 coin flips → 70/30 split possible; 10,000 flips → approaches 50/50
- **Ed Thorp** used the LLN to gain edge at blackjack, then applied it to
  Wall Street trading — foundation of most quant formulas

### Statistical Arbitrage

- Trading strategy using computers to track relationships between hundreds or
  thousands of stocks simultaneously
- Bets that when a long-term relationship temporarily breaks down, it will **revert**
- First deployed by computer programmer **Gerry Bamberger** at **Morgan Stanley**
  in the 1980s
- Quickly became one of the most powerful trading methods ever devised;
  helped launch **D. E. Shaw** and other major quant funds
- **Peter Muller** at Morgan Stanley's **Process Driven Trading** was among the
  most skilled stat arb practitioners
- Strategy **imploded in the quant crisis of August 2007** as simultaneous
  unwinding caused correlations to break down across funds

